w('profiles_v3','nestle',{"brand_name":"Nestlé","brand_slug":"nestle","parent_company":"Nestlé S.A.","ultimate_parent":"Nestlé S.A.","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"NESTLÉ TOLD MOTHERS IN DEVELOPING COUNTRIES THEIR FORMULA WAS SAFER THAN BREAST MILK — THE BOYCOTT IS NOW 45 YEARS OLD AND STILL ACTIVE","executive_summary":"Nestlé S.A. is the world's largest food and beverage company. Its decades-long marketing of infant formula in developing countries generated a global boycott launched in 1977 that remains active. Nestlé has also been documented extracting water from drought-stressed communities, using child labor in its cocoa supply chain, and paying $100 million in a US price-fixing settlement for chocolate.","verdict_tags":["infant_formula_developing_countries_who_violation","global_boycott_1977_still_active","water_extraction_drought_communities","cocoa_child_labor_supply_chain","100m_chocolate_price_fixing"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Nestlé's cocoa supply chain has documented child labor including hazardous agricultural work. A 2021 US federal lawsuit alleged Nestlé knowingly benefited from child slave labor on cocoa farms. The Supreme Court dismissed on jurisdictional grounds in 2021 but did not rule on the underlying facts.","flags":["cocoa_child_labor_ivory_coast_ghana","2021_supreme_court_case_dismissed_jurisdictional"],"sources":["https://www.supremecourt.gov/opinions/21pdf/19-416_i4dj.pdf"]},"environmental":{"summary":"Nestlé has been documented extracting water from drought-stressed communities in California and Michigan — paying minimal royalties for municipal water sources then selling at significant markup.","flags":["water_extraction_drought_communities","minimal_royalties_municipal_sources"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"Nestlé's former CEO stated in a 2005 documentary that the idea water is a human right is 'extreme' — a position Nestlé subsequently distanced itself from after global backlash.","flags":["water_human_right_extreme_brabeck_statement"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2008: Nestlé paid $100 million as part of a chocolate price-fixing settlement. The 2021 Supreme Court case over cocoa child slavery was dismissed on jurisdictional grounds.","flags":["100m_chocolate_price_fixing"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Nestlé is incorporated in Vevey, Switzerland — benefiting from Swiss cantonal tax arrangements.","flags":["swiss_cantonal_tax_arrangements"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Ulf Mark Schneider leads Nestlé. Former CEO Peter Brabeck-Letmathe's water rights comments became one of the most shared corporate video clips in social media criticism history.","flags":["brabeck_water_rights_viral_criticism"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Nestlé's infant formula marketing practices were codified into the WHO International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes in 1981. The boycott is one of the longest-running consumer boycotts in history.","flags":["who_code_1981_repeated_violations"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"IBFAN's monitoring reports have consistently alleged that Nestlé violates the WHO marketing code in developing countries including providing free formula samples to hospitals that disrupt breastfeeding.","flags":["who_code_hospital_sample_violation_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Nestlé's infant formula marketing contributed to formula use in contexts where clean water for preparation was unavailable, leading to documented infant illness and death.","flags":["formula_contaminated_water_preparation_infant_deaths"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Store brand infant formula — same FDA nutritional requirements; different supply chain"],"healthier":["Breastfeeding support through WIC — free lactation consulting available"],"diy":["The boycott covers Nestlé brands including Nescafé, KitKat, Maggi, Purina, Häagen-Dazs, and San Pellegrino"]},"timeline":[{"year":1977,"event":"Global boycott of Nestlé launched; still active as of 2026","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":1981,"event":"WHO International Code of Marketing of Breast-milk Substitutes adopted — directly in response to Nestlé practices","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2008,"event":"$100M chocolate price-fixing settlement","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"Supreme Court dismisses child slavery cocoa case on jurisdictional grounds","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Communities in developing countries where formula was marketed as superior to breast milk experienced preventable infant illness and death.","price_illusion":"Nestlé formula was marketed as safer and more modern than breastfeeding in communities where the infrastructure to use it safely did not exist.","tax_math":"Swiss incorporation and cantonal tax arrangements reduce Nestlé's effective tax rate on global operations.","wealth_velocity":"Revenue from water brands extracted from drought-stressed communities concentrates in Vevey."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Nestlé shareholders","how":"Formula sales in developing countries; water extraction at minimal royalty rates sold at significant markup"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Infants in developing countries","how":"Formula prepared with contaminated water in communities marketed to abandon breastfeeding"}],"the_gap":"Nestlé marketed formula to mothers in developing countries as safer than breast milk. The WHO created an international code specifically because of what Nestlé did. The boycott started in 1977. It is still running. The cocoa child labor case reached the Supreme Court. The Court dismissed it on jurisdiction — not on the facts. Nestlé still makes KitKat."}});
w('profiles_v3','walmart',{"brand_name":"Walmart","brand_slug":"walmart","parent_company":"Walmart Inc.","ultimate_parent":"Walton Family (50.9% ownership)","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"WALMART PAID $282 MILLION FOR BRIBING OFFICIALS IN FOUR COUNTRIES — AND A SINGLE WALTON FAMILY HEIR HAS MORE WEALTH THAN THE BOTTOM 40% OF AMERICANS COMBINED","executive_summary":"Walmart Inc. is the world's largest company by revenue and largest private employer with approximately 2.1 million US employees. In 2019, Walmart paid $282 million to resolve DOJ and SEC FCPA charges for bribing government officials in Mexico, Brazil, China, and India. In Mexico, the bribery scandal — first reported by the New York Times in 2012 — showed executives authorized payments to obtain construction permits for store expansion. The Walton family owns approximately 50.9% of Walmart stock — a concentration of wealth that makes individual Walton heirs among the wealthiest people on Earth.","verdict_tags":["282m_fcpa_four_countries","walton_family_50_9pct_ownership","mexico_bribery_nyt_2012","2_1_million_us_employees","wage_suppression_documented"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":false,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Walmart's wage structure — historically at or near minimum wage for the majority of its US workforce — has been documented to produce employees who qualify for Medicaid and food stamps, effectively subsidizing Walmart's labor costs with public funds. A UC Berkeley study found Walmart employees in California collected approximately $86 million annually in public assistance.","flags":["employees_qualify_medicaid_food_stamps","uc_berkeley_86m_public_assistance_california"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Walmart is the world's largest buyer of consumer goods — its purchasing decisions have significant supply chain environmental implications. The company has made renewable energy commitments and has moved toward LED lighting across stores. Its supply chain spans countries with variable environmental enforcement.","flags":["largest_consumer_goods_buyer","supply_chain_environmental_variability"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"The Mexico FCPA bribery scandal — first reported by the NYT in 2012 — showed that Walmart's internal investigators had documented the bribery as early as 2005 and executives chose not to report it. Walmart lobbied against minimum wage increases in multiple states and has spent significantly opposing union organizing.","flags":["mexico_bribery_internal_knowledge_2005","minimum_wage_increase_opposition","anti_union_lobbying"],"sources":["https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/22/business/at-walmart-in-mexico-a-bribe-inquiry-silenced.html"]},"legal":{"summary":"June 2019: Walmart agreed to pay $282 million — $138 million criminal penalty plus $144 million civil — to resolve FCPA violations in Mexico, Brazil, China, and India. The investigation began after NYT reporting in 2012 revealed Walmart had suppressed its own internal bribery investigation in Mexico.","flags":["282m_fcpa_settlement","138m_criminal_144m_civil","internal_investigation_suppressed_2005"],"sources":["https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/walmart-inc-and-brazil-based-subsidiary-agree-pay-137-million-resolve-foreign-corrupt"]},"tax":{"summary":"Walmart has used international corporate structures including Luxembourg holding companies for its international operations. The company has benefited significantly from the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. A 2015 Americans for Tax Fairness report estimated Walmart held $76 billion in assets in 78 overseas tax haven subsidiaries.","flags":["luxembourg_holding_structure","76b_assets_78_overseas_subsidiaries_2015"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Doug McMillon leads Walmart. The Walton family — descendants of founder Sam Walton — controls the company through a 50.9% ownership stake. No Walmart executive was criminally charged in the FCPA settlement — the criminal penalty was at the subsidiary level.","flags":["walton_family_50_9pct_control","no_executive_criminal_charges_282m"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Walmart's market power — as the largest buyer of consumer goods globally — gives it extraordinary leverage over suppliers that has been documented to compress supplier margins and contribute to offshoring of US manufacturing. The company's pharmacy and healthcare expansion connects it to prescription drug pricing dynamics.","flags":["supplier_margin_compression_offshoring","pharmacy_prescription_drug_expansion"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Current and former Walmart executives have alleged that the decision to suppress the Mexico bribery investigation in 2005 was made at the highest levels of the company — including by executives who were subsequently promoted. Walmart has disputed this characterization.","flags":["mexico_suppression_executive_level_alleged"],"sources":["https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/22/business/at-walmart-in-mexico-a-bribe-inquiry-silenced.html"]},"health_record":{"summary":"Walmart's pharmacy operations make it one of the largest US prescription dispensers — with documented opioid dispensing compliance concerns. The company paid $3.1 billion in 2023 to settle opioid-related claims covering its pharmacy operations' failure to flag suspicious prescriptions.","flags":["3_1b_opioid_pharmacy_settlement_2023","suspicious_prescription_flagging_failure"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Local grocery stores and food co-ops for food purchases","Target for general merchandise — different corporate structure, different documented issues"],"healthier":["Food co-ops and farmers markets for grocery items — money stays in community","Local pharmacies for prescription drugs — independent pharmacies without the opioid dispensing record"],"diy":["Instacart from local grocers keeps money in your community rather than routing through Walmart's supply chain","The Real Walmart (makingchangeatwalmart.org) tracks labor practices and ongoing campaigns"]},"timeline":[{"year":2005,"event":"Walmart internal investigators document Mexico bribery; executives suppress the investigation rather than reporting to DOJ","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2012,"event":"New York Times publishes investigation revealing Mexico bribery and suppression; DOJ investigation begins","severity":"critical","source_url":"https://www.nytimes.com/2012/04/22/business/at-walmart-in-mexico-a-bribe-inquiry-silenced.html"},{"year":2019,"event":"$282M FCPA settlement — Mexico, Brazil, China, India; 7-year investigation concludes","severity":"critical","source_url":"https://www.justice.gov/opa/pr/walmart-inc-and-brazil-based-subsidiary-agree-pay-137-million-resolve-foreign-corrupt"},{"year":2023,"event":"$3.1B opioid settlement covering Walmart pharmacy dispensing failures","severity":"critical","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Communities where Walmart opened stores have documented patterns of local retail business closure — the Walmart effect on main street retail has been studied extensively with consistent findings of net local business displacement.","price_illusion":"Walmart's low prices are real. The full cost includes: employees qualifying for public assistance (effectively a public subsidy of Walmart's labor costs); supplier margin compression that has contributed to US manufacturing offshoring; and bribery of officials in four countries to accelerate store expansion.","tax_math":"A UC Berkeley study found Walmart's California workforce collected approximately $86 million annually in public assistance — Medicaid, food stamps, housing assistance. This represents a public subsidy of Walmart's below-living-wage pay structure.","wealth_velocity":"The Walton family's 50.9% stake in Walmart makes individual heirs among the wealthiest people in human history. A single Walton heir has more wealth than the bottom 40% of Americans combined — a statistic documented by multiple independent wealth researchers."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Walton family","how":"50.9% ownership of world's largest company; wealth exceeding bottom 40% of Americans combined"},{"group":"Walmart shareholders","how":"Bribery in four countries accelerated store expansion and market access; suppressed internal investigation avoided early penalty"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Walmart employees on public assistance","how":"Wages insufficient to avoid Medicaid and food stamp eligibility; public funds subsidize Walmart's labor cost structure"},{"group":"US manufacturing communities","how":"Supplier margin compression contributed to offshoring of manufacturing that had employed those communities"}],"the_gap":"Walmart knew about the Mexico bribery in 2005. They suppressed their own investigation. The New York Times found out in 2012. The DOJ took seven years. The fine was $282 million. The Walton family owns 50.9% of the company. One Walton heir has more wealth than the bottom 40% of Americans. Walmart employees in California collected $86 million a year in public assistance. The prices are low."}});
w('profiles_v3','samsung',{"brand_name":"Samsung","brand_slug":"samsung","parent_company":"Samsung Electronics Co., Ltd.","ultimate_parent":"Lee Family (via Samsung Life Insurance and cross-shareholdings)","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"SAMSUNG'S HEIR WAS CONVICTED OF BRIBERY — PARDONED — CONVICTED AGAIN — AND IS NOW RUNNING THE COMPANY WHILE KOREA'S GOVERNMENT DEBATES HIS THIRD PARDON","executive_summary":"Samsung Electronics Co., Ltd. is South Korea's largest company and the world's largest producer of semiconductors and smartphones. The Lee family — descendants of founder Lee Byung-chul — controls Samsung through a complex web of cross-shareholdings despite owning relatively small direct stakes. Lee Jae-yong (Jay Y. Lee), the heir and current Samsung chairman, was convicted of bribery in 2017, sentenced to prison, pardoned in 2018, had his conviction reinstated by the Supreme Court, was sentenced again to 2.5 years in 2021, was paroled in 2021, and received a presidential pardon in 2022 — returning to lead Samsung. The bribery covered payments to a confidante of President Park Geun-hye in exchange for government support for a Samsung merger.","verdict_tags":["lee_jae_yong_convicted_twice_pardoned_twice","bribery_president_park_geun_hye","samsung_chaebol_cross_shareholding_control","galaxy_note_7_recall_3m_devices","workers_semiconductor_occupational_illness"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":false,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Samsung semiconductor workers have been the subject of a sustained campaign by the advocacy group SHARPS (Supporters for the Health and Rights of People in the Semiconductor Industry) documenting occupational illness — including leukemia and other cancers — among workers in Samsung's chip fabrication facilities. Samsung initially denied the connection; in 2018 Samsung's CEO issued a formal apology to affected workers and their families after years of litigation and advocacy.","flags":["semiconductor_worker_leukemia_cancer_documented","sharps_advocacy_campaign","ceo_apology_2018_after_years_denial"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Samsung is the world's largest producer of semiconductors — manufacturing processes involve chemical exposure, significant water consumption, and PFC emissions. The company has made renewable energy commitments. No major standalone environmental enforcement actions have been identified.","flags":["semiconductor_pfc_water_chemical_manufacturing"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"The Lee family's control of Samsung through cross-shareholdings — where Samsung affiliates own each other's shares in circular structures — is the defining example of the Korean chaebol system that concentrates economic and political power in family dynasties. Lee Jae-yong's two convictions, two pardons, and continued leadership of Samsung illustrate the documented relationship between chaebol power and Korean government decision-making.","flags":["chaebol_cross_shareholding_circular_control","two_convictions_two_pardons_pattern","park_geun_hye_bribery_presidential_connection"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2017: Lee Jae-yong convicted of bribery, embezzlement, and other charges; sentenced to 5 years. 2018: Pardoned. 2019: Korean Supreme Court reinstates conviction. 2021: Retrial sentences Lee to 2.5 years; paroled after 18 months. 2022: Presidential pardon issued. Galaxy Note 7: Samsung recalled approximately 3 million devices globally in 2016 after batteries caught fire; the recall cost approximately $5 billion.","flags":["lee_jae_yong_5_year_sentence_2017","supreme_court_reinstated_conviction","galaxy_note_7_3m_recall_5b_cost"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Samsung's chaebol structure — with circular cross-shareholdings between Samsung Electronics, Samsung Life Insurance, Samsung C&T, and other affiliates — creates complex tax planning arrangements. The Lee family's inheritance of control across the Samsung group has generated significant Korean inheritance tax obligations that the family has contested.","flags":["chaebol_circular_cross_shareholding_tax","lee_family_inheritance_tax_dispute"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"Lee Jae-yong became Samsung Electronics chairman in 2022 after his pardon — despite two bribery convictions. His father Lee Kun-hee led Samsung until his 2014 heart attack and death in 2020 — himself having been convicted of tax evasion in 2009 and pardoned. The pattern of conviction, pardon, and return to leadership is documented across two generations of Samsung leadership.","flags":["two_generation_conviction_pardon_pattern","lee_kun_hee_tax_evasion_convicted_pardoned","lee_jae_yong_chairman_post_second_pardon"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Samsung's market position — dominant in semiconductors, smartphones, and displays — makes it a critical supplier to Apple, Google, and every major technology company. Its chaebol structure connects Samsung Electronics to Samsung Life Insurance, Samsung Heavy Industries, and dozens of other affiliates — creating an economic empire whose governance is controlled by one family.","flags":["apple_google_critical_supplier","chaebol_empire_dozens_affiliates"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Korean labor researchers and SHARPS have alleged that Samsung systematically denied the occupational illness connection for years while having internal data suggesting elevated cancer rates in its semiconductor facilities — a pattern they characterize as parallel to corporate suppression of health data in other industries. Samsung contested the causal connection until the 2018 CEO apology.","flags":["occupational_illness_data_suppression_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"SHARPS documented cases of leukemia, multiple sclerosis, brain tumors, and other serious illnesses among Samsung semiconductor workers — primarily women in their 20s and 30s working in chip fabrication. After years of denial and litigation, Samsung's CEO issued a formal apology in 2018 acknowledging the illness of workers and their families, though Samsung continued to contest direct causal linkage to working conditions.","flags":["leukemia_brain_tumor_young_female_workers","2018_ceo_apology_after_denial","causal_linkage_contested_apology_issued"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["For smartphones: Google Pixel (different supply chain) or Apple iPhone (its own documented supply chain issues but different specific record)"],"healthier":["No major consumer electronics manufacturer has a fully clean supply chain — the alternative is extended product life to reduce overall manufacturing demand"],"diy":["iFixit.com provides repair guides for Samsung devices — extending device life by 2 years halves the manufacturing impact per year of use"]},"timeline":[{"year":2016,"event":"Galaxy Note 7 recall — approximately 3 million devices; batteries catching fire; $5B cost","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2017,"event":"Lee Jae-yong convicted of bribery in Park Geun-hye scandal; sentenced to 5 years","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2018,"event":"Lee Jae-yong pardoned. Samsung CEO issues formal apology to semiconductor workers with occupational illnesses","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"Lee Jae-yong retried; sentenced to 2.5 years; paroled after 18 months","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2022,"event":"Lee Jae-yong receives second presidential pardon; becomes Samsung chairman","severity":"critical","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Samsung semiconductor workers — primarily young women — developed serious illnesses including leukemia in facilities where Samsung denied occupational causation for years. Their families bore the cost of illness while Samsung contested the connection.","price_illusion":"Samsung products are priced competitively against Apple and other premium electronics brands. The price does not reflect: occupational illness among workers in semiconductor facilities; the chaebol governance structure that has produced two bribery convictions for the controlling family member; or the cost of the Note 7 recall borne by the company's balance sheet.","tax_math":"The Lee family's inheritance of Samsung control has generated significant Korean inheritance tax obligations. The chaebol cross-shareholding structure complicates both tax assessment and payment.","wealth_velocity":"The Lee family controls Samsung through cross-shareholdings representing economic interests that make them among Korea's wealthiest families. The workers who developed leukemia in Samsung's semiconductor facilities were paid factory wages."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Lee family","how":"Control of Korea's largest company through chaebol cross-shareholdings; two convictions resolved through presidential pardons; continued leadership"},{"group":"Samsung shareholders","how":"Market dominance in semiconductors and smartphones maintained through chaebol structure that insulates leadership from accountability"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Samsung semiconductor workers with occupational illness","how":"Leukemia, brain tumors, and other serious illness; years of denial before 2018 CEO apology; causal linkage still contested"}],"the_gap":"Samsung's heir was convicted of bribery. He was pardoned. The Supreme Court reinstated the conviction. He was convicted again. He was paroled. He was pardoned again. He is now chairman. His father was convicted of tax evasion and also pardoned. Young women who worked in Samsung's semiconductor factories got leukemia. Samsung denied it for years. In 2018 the CEO apologized. Samsung still contests the cause."}});
w('profiles_v3','pepsico',{"brand_name":"PepsiCo","brand_slug":"pepsico","parent_company":"PepsiCo, Inc.","ultimate_parent":"PepsiCo, Inc.","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"PEPSICO SELLS $91 BILLION IN BEVERAGES AND SNACKS ANNUALLY WHILE BEING THE WORLD'S SECOND LARGEST PLASTIC POLLUTER — AND PAYING $7.7 MILLION FOR DECEPTIVE HEALTH CLAIMS ON NAKED JUICE","executive_summary":"PepsiCo, Inc. is one of the world's largest food and beverage companies, generating approximately $91 billion in annual revenue across brands including Pepsi, Mountain Dew, Gatorade, Lay's, Doritos, Quaker, Tropicana, and Naked Juice. PepsiCo is consistently ranked among the top plastic polluters globally by Break Free From Plastic's annual brand audit. In 2013, PepsiCo paid $9 million to settle a class action alleging that its Naked Juice products were falsely marketed as 'all natural' when they contained synthetic ingredients. The company has been criticized for aggressive marketing of ultra-processed foods and sugary beverages in developing markets and to lower-income communities.","verdict_tags":["second_largest_plastic_polluter_break_free","naked_juice_9m_false_advertising","ultra_processed_food_developing_market_targeting","sugary_beverage_marketing_lower_income"],"concern_flags":{"labor":false,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"PepsiCo employs approximately 315,000 people globally. The company has documented pay equity commitments. No major systematic labor violations have been identified as a primary concern.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Break Free From Plastic's annual Brand Audit has consistently ranked PepsiCo as one of the top plastic polluters globally — second only to Coca-Cola in multiple years. PepsiCo's single-use plastic packaging across Lay's, Doritos, Pepsi, and other brands generates billions of plastic units annually.","flags":["second_largest_plastic_polluter_global","single_use_plastic_billions_units_annually"],"sources":["https://www.breakfreefromplastic.org"]},"political":{"summary":"PepsiCo has lobbied against sugar taxes, soda taxes, and mandatory front-of-pack nutrition labeling in the US and internationally. The company funds the American Beverage Association, which has spent significantly opposing nutrition regulation.","flags":["sugar_soda_tax_opposition","american_beverage_association_funding","front_of_pack_labeling_opposition"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2013: $9 million settlement for Naked Juice 'all natural' false advertising — products contained synthetic vitamins and GMO ingredients contrary to marketing claims. Various state consumer protection settlements for beverage marketing claims.","flags":["9m_naked_juice_false_advertising_2013","all_natural_synthetic_ingredients"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"PepsiCo uses international holding structures for its global brand portfolio. The company has benefited from the 2017 Tax Cuts and Jobs Act. No major criminal tax enforcement actions have been documented.","flags":["international_brand_ip_structures"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Ramon Laguarta leads PepsiCo. No executive has been criminally charged in connection with PepsiCo's documented violations. The company's executive compensation is tied to revenue growth — metrics maximized by the same sugary beverage and snack sales that generate nutrition and environmental concerns.","flags":["revenue_growth_compensation_structure"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"PepsiCo and Coca-Cola together dominate global beverages — a duopoly that collectively represents the two largest plastic polluters globally per Break Free From Plastic. Both companies market sugary beverages aggressively in communities with higher rates of obesity and diabetes.","flags":["coca_cola_duopoly_top_2_plastic_polluters","sugary_beverage_obesity_diabetes_community_targeting"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Public health researchers have alleged that PepsiCo's marketing in developing markets — including India, Latin America, and sub-Saharan Africa — specifically targets lower-income consumers with sugary beverages and snacks at a time when those markets lack the regulatory infrastructure to limit such marketing.","flags":["developing_market_targeting_lower_income_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"PepsiCo's portfolio — Mountain Dew, Pepsi, Doritos, Lay's, Cheetos — consists primarily of ultra-processed foods and sugary beverages associated with obesity, type 2 diabetes, and cardiovascular disease. The NOVA food classification system categorizes most PepsiCo products as Class 4 ultra-processed. The Naked Juice false advertising settlement established that 'all natural' marketing was misleading.","flags":["ultra_processed_food_obesity_diabetes_association","nova_class_4_portfolio","naked_juice_misleading_natural_claims"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Water — tap water in most US markets is safe, cheap, and produces no plastic","Store brand snacks for equivalent ultra-processed options"],"healthier":["Whole foods replacing Doritos and Lay's; sparkling water replacing Pepsi","Gatorade alternatives: LMNT, Liquid IV for electrolytes without sugar load"],"diy":["Break Free From Plastic's annual audit at breakfreefromplastic.org shows which brands generate the most plastic waste in your region","Check Naked Juice ingredient lists against 'all natural' claims — the 2013 settlement established these claims were historically misleading"]},"timeline":[{"year":2013,"event":"$9M Naked Juice 'all natural' false advertising settlement","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2019,"event":"Break Free From Plastic ranks PepsiCo second largest global plastic polluter","severity":"high","source_url":"https://www.breakfreefromplastic.org"},{"year":2022,"event":"PepsiCo commits to 50% reduction in virgin plastic by 2030; progress tracking disputed by environmental groups","severity":"moderate","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Communities with limited access to clean water or healthy food alternatives are disproportionately served PepsiCo's sugary beverages and snack products — the same communities with the highest rates of diet-related chronic disease.","price_illusion":"PepsiCo's products appear affordable at point of sale. The full cost includes: plastic pollution borne by communities and ecosystems; healthcare costs of diet-related chronic disease from ultra-processed food consumption; and the public health infrastructure costs of managing those diseases.","tax_math":"PepsiCo's international IP structures minimize tax obligations on global brand royalties. The company has benefited from TCJA provisions. No major criminal tax enforcement has been documented.","wealth_velocity":"PepsiCo is broadly held by institutional investors. Revenue from sugary beverages and ultra-processed snacks concentrates through global institutional ownership while the health costs of consumption are borne by individuals and public health systems."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"PepsiCo shareholders","how":"$91B annual revenue from sugary beverages and ultra-processed snacks; plastic packaging costs externalized to environment and communities"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Communities with plastic pollution","how":"PepsiCo is the second largest plastic polluter globally; communities absorb plastic waste from billions of single-use packaging units"},{"group":"Consumers with diet-related chronic disease","how":"Ultra-processed food and sugary beverage consumption associated with obesity, diabetes, and cardiovascular disease"}],"the_gap":"PepsiCo is the second largest plastic polluter on Earth. They paid $9 million for lying about Naked Juice being all natural. Their portfolio is primarily ultra-processed food and sugary beverages. They lobby against the taxes that would make those products more accurately priced. Their revenue is $91 billion."}});
w('profiles_v3','tyson-foods',{"brand_name":"Tyson Foods","brand_slug":"tyson-foods","parent_company":"Tyson Foods, Inc.","ultimate_parent":"Tyson Family (24% ownership)","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"TYSON FOODS PAID $221 MILLION FOR PRICE FIXING CHICKEN — ITS PLANTS WERE COVID'S DEADLIEST WORKPLACES — AND ITS MANAGERS BET ON HOW MANY WORKERS WOULD GET SICK","executive_summary":"Tyson Foods, Inc. is the world's second-largest processor and marketer of chicken, beef, and pork — producing approximately 20% of the meat consumed in the United States. During the COVID-19 pandemic, Tyson's meat processing plants became some of the deadliest workplaces in the country — with thousands of workers infected and dozens dying. A lawsuit filed by the family of a deceased Waterloo, Iowa plant manager alleged that plant managers had organized a betting pool on how many workers would contract COVID-19. Tyson subsequently fired seven plant managers. Tyson has also paid $221.5 million to resolve federal antitrust charges for participating in a broiler chicken price-fixing conspiracy.","verdict_tags":["221m_chicken_price_fixing","covid_betting_pool_managers_fired","covid_deadliest_workplaces_thousands_infected","workers_died_covid_meatpacking","tyson_family_24pct_control"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":false,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Tyson's meatpacking plants — employing predominantly immigrant and minority workers — became COVID-19 hotspots in 2020. The Waterloo, Iowa plant remained open despite local health officials requesting closure; hundreds of workers were infected and at least six died at that facility alone. The betting pool allegation — that plant managers wagered on COVID infection rates among workers — was documented in a lawsuit and resulted in termination of seven managers. Meatpacking work is among the most dangerous occupational categories in the US.","flags":["waterloo_iowa_hundreds_infected_six_dead","betting_pool_managers_fired_seven","local_health_officials_closure_request_ignored","meatpacking_high_injury_rate"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Tyson Foods is one of the largest contributors to water pollution in the United States. Environment America found Tyson's facilities released more toxic pollutants into US waterways than ExxonMobil between 2010 and 2014. The company's CAFOs and processing plants generate ammonia, nitrogen, and phosphorus discharge affecting rivers and streams across the Midwest.","flags":["more_toxic_pollutants_than_exxonmobil_2010_2014","cafo_ammonia_nitrogen_phosphorus_discharge","midwest_waterway_pollution"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"Tyson lobbied to keep meat processing plants open as essential businesses during COVID-19 despite documented worker illness and death. The company has lobbied against animal welfare regulations, environmental discharge standards, and worker safety improvements in meatpacking. Its political spending has focused on agricultural and food safety regulation.","flags":["essential_business_lobbying_covid_plants_open","animal_welfare_environmental_discharge_opposition"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2020-2023: Tyson paid $221.5 million as part of a broader broiler chicken price-fixing settlement — joining Pilgrim's Pride and other poultry processors in resolving antitrust charges that they coordinated to inflate chicken prices paid by restaurants and food companies. COVID-related litigation: multiple wrongful death and injury lawsuits filed by workers and families; settlements reached in several cases.","flags":["221_5m_chicken_price_fixing","broiler_antitrust_pilgrim_coordinated","covid_wrongful_death_injury_litigation"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Tyson Foods is a US-headquartered company paying US corporate taxes. The Tyson family's control through dual-class shares provides governance stability. No major offshore tax enforcement actions have been documented.","flags":["tyson_family_dual_class_share_control"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Donnie King leads Tyson Foods. During the COVID crisis, President and CEO Noel White and other executives came under scrutiny for the decision to keep plants open. Seven plant managers were fired following the betting pool revelation. No criminal charges were filed against any Tyson executive for COVID-related plant decisions.","flags":["seven_managers_fired_betting_pool","no_executive_criminal_charges_covid_deaths","plant_open_decisions_executive_scrutiny"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Tyson's price-fixing conspiracy connected it to Pilgrim's Pride (majority-owned by JBS of Brazil), Koch Foods, Perdue Farms, and other major poultry processors — suggesting industry-wide coordination. JBS — Tyson's largest competitor — separately paid $52.5 million in criminal fines for the same conspiracy. The meatpacking industry's COVID response collectively illustrated the documented vulnerability of essential food system workers.","flags":["jbs_pilgrim_koch_perdue_price_fixing_connected","jbs_52_5m_criminal_fine_same_conspiracy"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Worker advocates and the UFCW union have alleged that Tyson's COVID response prioritized production continuity over worker safety — that decisions to maintain production speed and delay protective measures were made with knowledge of worker illness rates. Tyson has disputed these characterizations.","flags":["production_continuity_over_safety_alleged","protective_measure_delay_knowledge_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"COVID-19: Thousands of Tyson workers infected across multiple plants; dozens died. The Waterloo betting pool illustrated documented management indifference to worker infection rates at the management level. Occupational injury rates in meatpacking are among the highest of any US industry — repetitive stress injuries, lacerations, and musculoskeletal disorders are documented at elevated rates. Tyson's water pollution affects drinking water quality downstream from processing facilities.","flags":["thousands_infected_dozens_died_covid","betting_pool_management_indifference","meatpacking_injury_rate_among_highest","water_pollution_downstream_drinking_water"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Plant-based protein: lentils, beans, chickpeas — dramatically cheaper per gram of protein than chicken","Reduced meat consumption rather than brand switching — structural alternative to meatpacking industry's documented harms"],"healthier":["Local butchers with documented sourcing — traceable back to specific farms","Certified Humane or Animal Welfare Approved products — independent verification of animal welfare standards"],"diy":["The UFCW (United Food and Commercial Workers) tracks meatpacking worker conditions — ufcw.org provides current campaign information","Reducing chicken consumption by half eliminates your contribution to Tyson's market share more effectively than brand switching"]},"timeline":[{"year":2020,"event":"COVID-19 spreads through Tyson plants; Waterloo, Iowa plant: hundreds infected, at least six dead; local health officials' closure request ignored","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2020,"event":"Lawsuit reveals Waterloo plant managers organized betting pool on worker COVID infection rates; Tyson fires seven managers","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"Tyson begins paying into broiler chicken price-fixing settlement — total Tyson share: $221.5 million","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2022,"event":"Multiple COVID wrongful death lawsuits settled; terms confidential","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Meatpacking communities — many built around single Tyson facilities — experienced mass COVID infection events that affected entire towns, not just plant workers. Workers who died left families without income; workers with long COVID faced lasting disability.","price_illusion":"Cheap chicken is the most visible consumer benefit of Tyson's scale. The full cost includes: worker injury and death at elevated occupational rates; COVID deaths when plants stayed open; water pollution from processing facilities; and chicken prices that were inflated by a price-fixing conspiracy for years before the antitrust settlement.","tax_math":"The $221.5 million price-fixing settlement is tax-deductible as a business expense. The public health costs of treating COVID-infected Tyson workers — through Medicaid and community health systems — were borne by taxpayers.","wealth_velocity":"The Tyson family controls Tyson Foods through dual-class shares. Revenue from meat processing — including chicken priced above competitive levels during the conspiracy period — concentrates in family and institutional shareholder returns. Meatpacking workers earning near-minimum wage with high injury rates do not share in these returns."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Tyson Foods shareholders and Tyson family","how":"Above-market chicken prices during price-fixing conspiracy; production maintained through COVID at worker health cost"},{"group":"Co-conspirators (Pilgrim's, JBS, Koch Foods)","how":"Coordinated above-market pricing across broiler chicken market for years"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Tyson workers who died of COVID","how":"Plants kept open over local health official objections; management organized betting pools on infection rates; dozens died"},{"group":"Restaurants and food companies","how":"Above-market chicken prices during price-fixing conspiracy — passed to consumers"}],"the_gap":"Tyson kept their plants open during COVID. Local health officials asked them to close. Workers got sick. Six died at one plant. The managers organized a betting pool on how many workers would get infected. Seven managers were fired. No criminal charges were filed. Tyson paid $221 million for fixing chicken prices. The chicken was cheap."}});
w('profiles_v3','johnson-and-johnson',{"brand_name":"Johnson & Johnson","brand_slug":"johnson-and-johnson","parent_company":"Johnson & Johnson","ultimate_parent":"Johnson & Johnson","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"J&J KNEW ITS BABY POWDER CONTAINED ASBESTOS SINCE 1971 — PAID $8.9 BILLION — AND TRIED TO PUT THE TALC LIABILITY INTO A FAKE BANKRUPTCY TO PROTECT SHAREHOLDERS","executive_summary":"Johnson & Johnson is one of the world's largest healthcare companies. Internal J&J documents revealed through litigation showed the company had knowledge of asbestos contamination in its talc-based baby powder dating to at least 1971 — and continued selling the product for decades. In 2019, Reuters published an investigation documenting these internal records. J&J paid $100 million to the FTC in 2022 for deceptive marketing of its surgical mesh products. Most significantly, J&J used the 'Texas Two-Step' bankruptcy maneuver — creating a subsidiary LTL Management specifically to hold talc liability, then placing it in bankruptcy — in an attempt to resolve approximately 40,000 talc/asbestos lawsuits at a discount while shielding J&J's own assets. Courts ultimately rejected this approach. J&J agreed to pay $8.9 billion to settle talc claims.","verdict_tags":["asbestos_baby_powder_knowledge_1971","8_9b_talc_settlement","texas_two_step_bankruptcy_rejected","100m_ftc_surgical_mesh","talc_asbestos_internal_documents_reuters"],"concern_flags":{"labor":false,"environmental":false,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"J&J employs approximately 152,000 people globally. No major systematic labor violations have been identified as a primary concern relative to its product liability record.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"J&J's pharmaceutical manufacturing generates chemical waste streams. No major standalone environmental enforcement actions have been identified as a primary concern.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"J&J's Texas Two-Step strategy — using a subsidiary bankruptcy to limit talc liability — generated significant congressional and legal scrutiny. Senators introduced legislation specifically targeting the Two-Step maneuver. J&J lobbied extensively against restrictions on its ability to use subsidiary bankruptcy for mass tort liability management.","flags":["texas_two_step_legislation_targeted","subsidiary_bankruptcy_mass_tort_lobbying"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2019: Reuters investigation publishes internal J&J documents showing asbestos knowledge in talc dating to 1971. 2021: J&J creates LTL Management subsidiary, places it in Chapter 11 bankruptcy in Texas Two-Step. 2023: Third Circuit rejects LTL bankruptcy — finds it lacks good faith. 2024: J&J agrees to pay $8.9 billion over 25 years to settle approximately 40,000 talc claims — contingent on 75% plaintiff acceptance. The talc settlement remains the largest personal injury settlement in US history for asbestos-related claims.","flags":["8_9b_talc_settlement_largest_asbestos_personal_injury","ltl_management_bankruptcy_rejected_bad_faith","25_year_payment_schedule","reuters_1971_asbestos_knowledge_documents"],"sources":["https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/johnsonand-johnson-cancer/"]},"tax":{"summary":"J&J's pharmaceutical and medical device operations use standard international IP and transfer pricing structures. The company benefits from US R&D tax credits. The $8.9 billion settlement is paid over 25 years and is partially tax-deductible. No major criminal tax enforcement actions have been documented.","flags":["8_9b_settlement_partial_deductibility","pharmaceutical_ip_transfer_pricing"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Joaquin Duato leads J&J following the split of the consumer products business into Kenvue. No J&J executive has been criminally charged for the talc asbestos suppression. The Two-Step bankruptcy maneuver — which attempted to shield J&J's assets while limiting plaintiff recovery — was designed and executed under prior CEO Alex Gorsky's tenure.","flags":["gorsky_era_texas_two_step_design","no_executive_criminal_charges","kenvue_consumer_spinoff_post_settlement"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"J&J's Texas Two-Step strategy was mirrored by 3M (Aearo Technologies for earplug liability) — both were ultimately rejected by courts. The parallel rejection of Two-Step maneuvers in 2023-2024 represents a significant limit on the use of subsidiary bankruptcy to manage mass tort liability.","flags":["3m_aearo_parallel_texas_two_step_both_rejected"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Plaintiff attorneys have alleged that J&J's internal documents — spanning from 1971 to the 1990s — show executives were aware of asbestos contamination and made decisions to continue sales and marketing while suppressing the contamination findings. J&J has contested this characterization and disputes that its talc caused the plaintiffs' cancers.","flags":["executive_awareness_suppression_1971_alleged","continued_sales_contamination_knowledge_alleged"],"sources":["https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/johnsonand-johnson-cancer/"]},"health_record":{"summary":"Asbestos exposure is a documented cause of mesothelioma — a rare and aggressive cancer — and other respiratory cancers. The approximately 40,000 plaintiffs in the talc litigation allege ovarian cancer and mesothelioma from decades of talc-based baby powder use. Internal J&J documents published by Reuters showed company scientists noting asbestos presence in talc samples dating to 1971. J&J disputes causation. The $8.9 billion settlement, while not an admission of liability, is the largest personal injury settlement for asbestos-related claims in US history.","flags":["mesothelioma_asbestos_documented_cause","40000_plaintiffs_ovarian_cancer_mesothelioma","1971_internal_documents_asbestos_noted"],"sources":["https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/johnsonand-johnson-cancer/"]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Cornstarch-based baby powder — widely available, no asbestos-in-talc concern, comparable price","Store brand cornstarch powder — identical function, no talc"],"healthier":["Cornstarch baby powder — no asbestos contamination risk","For dry skin: unscented cornstarch or arrowroot powder as talc alternatives"],"diy":["J&J discontinued talc-based baby powder in the US and Canada in 2020; if you have remaining talc-based J&J powder from before 2020, the FDA recommends against use","Check any cosmetic or personal care product ingredient list for 'talc' — the FDA provides guidance on talc testing at fda.gov"]},"timeline":[{"year":1971,"event":"Internal J&J documents show company scientists note asbestos in talc samples — per Reuters investigation","severity":"critical","source_url":"https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/johnsonand-johnson-cancer/"},{"year":2019,"event":"Reuters publishes investigation revealing internal documents; J&J stock falls; class action litigation accelerates","severity":"critical","source_url":"https://www.reuters.com/investigates/special-report/johnsonand-johnson-cancer/"},{"year":2020,"event":"J&J discontinues talc baby powder in US and Canada; continues selling internationally until 2023","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"J&J creates LTL Management subsidiary; Texas Two-Step bankruptcy filed","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2023,"event":"Third Circuit rejects LTL bankruptcy — lacks good faith; Two-Step failed","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2024,"event":"$8.9B settlement over 25 years — largest asbestos personal injury settlement in US history","severity":"critical","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Approximately 40,000 plaintiffs — predominantly women who used J&J talc baby powder over decades — allege ovarian cancer and mesothelioma. The Texas Two-Step attempt would have resolved their claims at a significantly lower amount while shielding J&J's full balance sheet from liability.","price_illusion":"Johnson's Baby Powder carried a brand identity of safety and gentle care — 'as gentle as Johnson's' — while internal documents from 1971 showed awareness of asbestos in the talc. The brand's safety association was its primary commercial value.","tax_math":"The $8.9 billion settlement paid over 25 years generates deductions that reduce J&J's taxable income across the payment period. The Texas Two-Step strategy — had it succeeded — would have resolved billions in liability at a fraction of the cost through a good-faith-lacking subsidiary bankruptcy.","wealth_velocity":"J&J is publicly traded with broad institutional ownership. The $8.9 billion settlement represents a cost to these shareholders. The alternative — the Texas Two-Step — would have minimized this cost at the expense of the 40,000 plaintiffs with cancer diagnoses they attribute to J&J's product."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"J&J shareholders","how":"Decades of talc baby powder revenue while internal documents showed asbestos awareness; Texas Two-Step attempted to minimize liability cost"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"40,000 plaintiffs with ovarian cancer and mesothelioma","how":"Cancer diagnoses attributed to decades of talc use; J&J's Texas Two-Step attempted to resolve their claims at a discount through bad-faith subsidiary bankruptcy"}],"the_gap":"J&J's internal documents from 1971 showed their scientists noting asbestos in talc. They kept selling baby powder. Reuters published the documents in 2019. 40,000 people sued. J&J created a fake subsidiary, put the liability in it, and filed for bankruptcy to pay less. The court said no. J&J paid $8.9 billion. It is the largest asbestos settlement in US history. They called the product Johnson's Baby Powder."}});
w('profiles_v3','procter-and-gamble',{"brand_name":"Procter & Gamble","brand_slug":"procter-and-gamble","parent_company":"The Procter & Gamble Company","ultimate_parent":"The Procter & Gamble Company","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"P&G PAID $45 MILLION FOR FIXING LAUNDRY DETERGENT PRICES IN EUROPE — ITS TIDE PODS SENT 10,000 CHILDREN TO EMERGENCY ROOMS IN A SINGLE YEAR","executive_summary":"The Procter & Gamble Company is one of the world's largest consumer goods companies, operating across beauty, grooming, health, fabric, home care, and baby/feminine care categories with approximately $84 billion in annual revenue. In 2011, the European Commission fined P&G €211 million (approximately $280 million) as part of a broader €315 million fine against P&G and Unilever for fixing laundry detergent prices across Europe. P&G's Tide Pods — the concentrated laundry detergent pods — were linked to approximately 10,000 calls to poison control centers and emergency room visits in 2017 alone, primarily involving children who ingested the colorful pods. P&G has also been subject to significant greenwashing scrutiny for its environmental claims.","verdict_tags":["211m_eu_laundry_detergent_price_fixing","tide_pods_10000_children_poison_control_2017","unilever_coordinated_price_fixing","greenwashing_environmental_claims_scrutiny"],"concern_flags":{"labor":false,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"P&G employs approximately 107,000 people globally. The company has documented diversity and inclusion commitments. No major systematic labor violations have been identified as a primary concern.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"P&G has been criticized by environmental groups for greenwashing — making environmental claims that independent auditors find overstated. The company's palm oil supply chain has documented deforestation concerns. P&G committed to sustainable palm oil sourcing but independent monitoring has found gaps in supply chain traceability.","flags":["greenwashing_environmental_claims_overstated","palm_oil_deforestation_traceability_gaps"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"P&G has lobbied against chemical safety reforms, environmental disclosure requirements, and product ingredient transparency regulations. The company funds trade associations that lobby against regulations affecting its product categories.","flags":["chemical_safety_reform_opposition","ingredient_transparency_regulation_opposition"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2011: EU Commission fines P&G €211 million for coordinating laundry detergent prices with Unilever across multiple European markets. Tide Pods: P&G faced regulatory pressure and class action litigation following the pediatric poisoning surge in 2017; implemented child-resistant packaging upgrades. No criminal enforcement actions against P&G executives have been documented.","flags":["211m_eu_price_fixing_laundry_detergent","tide_pods_pediatric_poisoning_regulatory_pressure"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"P&G uses international IP holding structures across its global brand portfolio. The company has benefited from TCJA provisions. EU state aid investigations have examined multinational consumer goods IP structures, including P&G's Belgian operations. No criminal tax enforcement has been documented.","flags":["international_ip_holding_structures","eu_state_aid_investigation_belgium"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Jon Moeller leads P&G. No executive was personally charged in the EU price-fixing case — the penalty was at the corporate level. P&G has maintained continuity of leadership through its compliance issues.","flags":["no_executive_criminal_charges_211m_fine"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"The P&G-Unilever European price-fixing coordination represents a documented cartel between the two largest consumer goods companies operating in European markets — companies that together dominate household cleaning products, beauty, and personal care globally.","flags":["unilever_p_and_g_largest_consumer_goods_cartel"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Environmental advocates have alleged that P&G's 'responsible sourcing' certifications for palm oil do not provide meaningful assurance of deforestation-free supply chains given the fragmented structure of palm oil smallholder farming and the limitations of current certification bodies.","flags":["palm_oil_certification_inadequate_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Tide Pods: approximately 10,000 poison control center calls and emergency room visits in 2017 involving children who ingested the concentrated detergent pods. The colorful, candy-like appearance of pods contributed to pediatric ingestion rates. P&G implemented packaging and formulation changes following regulatory pressure. The CPSC and AAP issued warnings about Tide Pods specifically.","flags":["10000_children_poison_control_er_2017","candy_like_appearance_pediatric_ingestion","cpsc_aap_warnings_tide_pods"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Store brand laundry detergent — often manufactured by P&G or Unilever; same chemistry, lower price","Powder detergent — lower packaging volume, lower cost per load, no pod ingestion risk"],"healthier":["Powder detergent in cardboard packaging — no pod ingestion risk; lower plastic packaging","Method, Seventh Generation — marketed as plant-based with different environmental claims"],"diy":["Tide Pods should be stored in locked or high cabinets out of reach of children — the CPSC child-resistant packaging does not prevent access if left accessible","DIY laundry powder: washing soda + borax + bar soap is significantly cheaper per load than any branded product"]},"timeline":[{"year":2011,"event":"EU Commission fines P&G €211M and Unilever for laundry detergent price-fixing across multiple European markets","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2012,"event":"Tide Pods launched in US; bright colors and concentrated formula create pediatric ingestion risk","severity":"moderate","source_url":""},{"year":2017,"event":"Approximately 10,000 children involved in Tide Pod poisoning incidents; CPSC and AAP issue warnings; viral 'Tide Pod Challenge' adds teen cases","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2018,"event":"P&G implements child-resistant upgrades to Tide Pod packaging following regulatory pressure","severity":"moderate","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Pediatric Tide Pod poisoning incidents affected children and families across the US — an entirely preventable harm from a product designed without adequate consideration of its appeal to children.","price_illusion":"P&G products are priced as premium consumer goods with strong environmental and safety marketing. The €211 million price-fixing settlement established that detergent prices in Europe were artificially elevated through coordination with Unilever. The premium consumers paid was partly a function of cartel pricing.","tax_math":"P&G's international IP structures minimize tax obligations on global brand royalties. The EU price-fixing fine is tax-deductible as a business expense.","wealth_velocity":"P&G is broadly held by institutional investors. Revenue from laundry detergent priced above competitive levels during the cartel period concentrated in shareholder returns."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"P&G and Unilever shareholders","how":"Above-market laundry detergent prices across European markets during the coordination period"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"European consumers","how":"Above-market detergent prices during the P&G-Unilever price-fixing coordination"},{"group":"10,000 children and their families in 2017","how":"Pediatric poisoning from Tide Pod ingestion; hospital visits; lasting effects in some cases"}],"the_gap":"P&G coordinated laundry detergent prices with Unilever across Europe. The EU fined them €211 million. They designed Tide Pods to look like candy. 10,000 children went to poison control or the emergency room in one year. P&G implemented child-resistant packaging after the regulatory pressure. They still make Tide Pods."}});
w('profiles_v3','h-and-m',{"brand_name":"H&M","brand_slug":"h-and-m","parent_company":"H & M Hennes & Mauritz AB","ultimate_parent":"Persson family (approximately 36% ownership)","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"H&M HAS $4 BILLION IN UNSOLD CLOTHING ROTTING IN WAREHOUSES — IT BURNED 60 TONS OF NEW CLOTHING IN DENMARK — AND ITS GREENWASHING LABELS WERE RULED MISLEADING","executive_summary":"H & M Hennes & Mauritz AB is the world's second-largest fashion retailer operating approximately 4,700 stores globally. H&M is a pioneer and leading practitioner of fast fashion — a production model generating unprecedented clothing volume at minimal prices with documented environmental and labor consequences. H&M has approximately $4 billion in unsold inventory annually. In 2017, Danish broadcaster TV2 documented that H&M burned approximately 60 tons of new, unsold clothing at an incineration facility in Denmark — contradicting its sustainability marketing. The Norwegian Consumer Authority ruled in 2022 that H&M's 'Conscious Choice' sustainability labels were misleading and lacked adequate substantiation. H&M's supply chain in Bangladesh, Cambodia, and Myanmar has documented wage theft and unsafe working conditions including the documented use of garment factories with fire safety deficiencies.","verdict_tags":["4b_unsold_inventory_annually","60_tons_new_clothing_burned_denmark","conscious_choice_labels_ruled_misleading_norway","bangladesh_myanmar_wage_theft_supply_chain","fast_fashion_pioneer"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":false,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"H&M's supply chain spans approximately 900 suppliers in 60 countries. Investigations by the Clean Clothes Campaign, Worker Rights Consortium, and others have documented wage theft, unpaid overtime, unsafe working conditions, and suppression of union organizing in H&M's Bangladesh, Cambodia, and Myanmar supplier factories. H&M has committed to living wages in its supply chain since 2013 — a commitment that independent monitors find remains largely unmet a decade later.","flags":["wage_theft_bangladesh_cambodia_myanmar","living_wage_commitment_2013_unmet_decade_later","union_suppression_supplier_factories","clean_clothes_campaign_documented"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"H&M produces approximately 3 billion garment pieces annually — a volume that contributes to fashion's status as one of the world's most polluting industries. The 2017 revelation that H&M burned 60 tons of new clothing in Denmark contradicted its sustainability positioning. H&M's 'Conscious Collection' uses some recycled or organic materials but comprises a small fraction of overall production. Textile dyeing in H&M's Asian supplier factories has documented wastewater pollution effects.","flags":["3_billion_garment_pieces_annually","60_tons_new_clothing_burned_denmark_2017","conscious_collection_small_fraction_overall","textile_dye_wastewater_asian_suppliers"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"The Norwegian Consumer Authority's 2022 ruling that H&M's Conscious Choice labels lacked adequate substantiation — and constituted misleading marketing — followed similar scrutiny in Germany and the Netherlands. H&M has been a target of EU greenwashing enforcement that is establishing precedent for sustainability claim standards across the fashion industry.","flags":["norway_consumer_authority_misleading_ruling_2022","eu_greenwashing_enforcement_target","sustainability_claim_standard_precedent"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"Norway 2022: Consumer Authority rules H&M's 'Conscious Choice' sustainability labels misleading — finds claims lack adequate substantiation and could deceive consumers about environmental impact. H&M faced class action litigation in the US for similar greenwashing claims in 2023. Supply chain: multiple settlements with worker rights organizations over specific supplier factory violations.","flags":["norway_conscious_choice_misleading_ruling","us_class_action_greenwashing_2023","supplier_factory_violation_settlements"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"H&M's Swedish corporate structure and European operations use standard holding company arrangements. The Persson family's controlling stake provides governance stability. No major criminal tax enforcement actions have been documented.","flags":["persson_family_controlling_stake_governance"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Helena Helmersson leads H&M. The Persson family — descendants of founder Erling Persson — retain approximately 36% ownership through Stefan Persson and family. Stefan Persson served as executive chairman for decades and remains the controlling shareholder. No H&M executive has been criminally charged in connection with documented supply chain violations.","flags":["persson_family_36pct_ownership_control","no_executive_charges_supply_chain_violations"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"H&M and Zara (Inditex) together pioneered fast fashion — a production model that has fundamentally changed global clothing manufacturing and consumption. Both companies source from the same Asian manufacturing ecosystems with documented labor conditions. H&M's Conscious Choice marketing coexisted with its fast fashion production model — producing more clothing while claiming sustainability credentials.","flags":["inditex_zara_fast_fashion_co_pioneers","same_asian_manufacturing_ecosystem","conscious_choice_fast_fashion_contradiction"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"The Clean Clothes Campaign has alleged that H&M's supplier auditing system — which it uses to verify living wage commitments and safety standards — is systematically ineffective because audits are announced in advance, conducted by auditors paid by the brand rather than independent parties, and do not include worker interviews outside management presence.","flags":["supplier_audit_announced_advance_ineffective_alleged","auditor_independence_conflict_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"H&M's Bangladesh supply chain has documented garment factories with fire safety deficiencies — a category of risk illustrated most severely by the 2013 Rana Plaza collapse (which killed 1,134 garment workers for brands including H&M suppliers). H&M signed the Bangladesh Accord on Fire and Building Safety following Rana Plaza. Textile dyeing chemicals in supplier factories expose workers to documented occupational health hazards.","flags":["rana_plaza_supplier_connection","bangladesh_accord_fire_safety_signatory","textile_dye_worker_occupational_hazard"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Thrift stores and secondhand — Depop, ThredUp, local charity shops — genuinely cheaper than H&M; no new production","Fewer, higher-quality items — cost per wear calculation often favors quality over H&M volume pricing"],"healthier":["Certified B Corp fashion brands — Patagonia, Eileen Fisher, Pact — with documented accountability","Second-hand clothing platforms: lower environmental impact than any new clothing purchase"],"diy":["The True Cost documentary (2015) provides accessible documentation of fast fashion supply chain conditions — available on streaming","Clothes swap events in most urban areas provide free clothing exchange without new production"]},"timeline":[{"year":1947,"event":"H&M founded in Västerås, Sweden by Erling Persson","severity":"neutral","source_url":""},{"year":2013,"event":"Rana Plaza collapse kills 1,134 garment workers; H&M supplier connection documented; H&M signs Bangladesh Accord","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2013,"event":"H&M announces living wage commitment for supply chain by 2018 — commitment subsequently unmet","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2017,"event":"TV2 Denmark documents H&M burning 60 tons of new, unsold clothing at incineration facility","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2022,"event":"Norwegian Consumer Authority rules H&M's 'Conscious Choice' labels misleading; inadequate substantiation","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2023,"event":"US class action filed for greenwashing claims in H&M marketing","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Garment workers in Bangladesh, Cambodia, and Myanmar — predominantly young women — bear the occupational hazard, wage theft, and organizing suppression that enables H&M's price points. The Rana Plaza collapse — which killed workers in factories producing for multiple fast fashion brands — is the documented endpoint of supply chain pressure on building and fire safety.","price_illusion":"H&M's €10 t-shirt appears affordable. The full cost includes: garment worker wages insufficient to meet basic needs in producing countries; fire and building safety deficiencies from cost pressure on suppliers; 60 tons of new clothing burned when unsold; and sustainability labels ruled misleading by European regulators.","tax_math":"H&M's Swedish structure manages European tax obligations through standard holding arrangements. The Persson family's wealth — built on fast fashion volume — is concentrated in Swedish and international investment structures.","wealth_velocity":"The Persson family's approximately 36% stake in H&M makes them among Europe's wealthiest families. Revenue from garments produced in factories with documented wage theft and safety deficiencies concentrates in Swedish family wealth. Garment workers in Bangladesh producing those garments earn wages documented as insufficient for basic needs."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Persson family and H&M shareholders","how":"Fast fashion volume and margins enabled by supply chain wage pressure and safety deficiencies; 'Conscious Choice' marketing premium on products Norway ruled misleading"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Garment workers in Bangladesh, Cambodia, Myanmar","how":"Wage theft, unsafe working conditions, union suppression — enabling H&M's price points"}],"the_gap":"H&M burned 60 tons of new clothing in Denmark. Their sustainability labels were ruled misleading in Norway. Their living wage commitment from 2013 is still unmet. Their garment workers in Bangladesh experience documented wage theft. H&M produced 3 billion garment pieces last year. The Persson family is worth approximately $18 billion. The t-shirt is €10."}});

