w('profiles_v4','vale',{"brand_name":"Vale","brand_slug":"vale","parent_company":"Vale S.A.","ultimate_parent":"Brazilian Federal Government (partial) and Previ pension fund","overall_concern_level":"significant","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"VALE OWNS TWO OF THE THREE WORST MINING DAM DISASTERS IN HISTORY — MARIANA 2015 AND BRUMADINHO 2019 — 272 PEOPLE DIED AND VALE STILL HASN'T FULLY COMPENSATED THE COMMUNITIES","executive_summary":"Vale S.A. is the world's largest iron ore producer and one of the world's largest mining companies, headquartered in Rio de Janeiro. Vale has been responsible for two of the most catastrophic mining dam failures in history. In November 2015, the Fundão tailings dam — jointly owned by Vale and BHP — failed at the Samarco mine in Mariana, Minas Gerais, killing 19 people and releasing 43 million cubic meters of iron ore mining waste into the Doce River — Brazil's longest river and an environmental catastrophe affecting hundreds of communities. In January 2019, Vale's Brumadinho tailings dam failed, releasing approximately 12 million cubic meters of mining waste that killed 272 people — the deadliest mining dam disaster in Brazilian history. Vale had received safety certifications for the Brumadinho dam weeks before its failure.","verdict_tags":["brumadinho_2019_272_dead_deadliest_mining_dam_brazil","mariana_2015_19_dead_doce_river_environmental_catastrophe","dam_certified_safe_weeks_before_failure","$7b_settlement_brumadinho","samarco_bhp_joint_venture_mariana"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":true,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"The Brumadinho dam failure killed 272 people — the majority of whom were Vale employees and contractors working at the mine site or in a cafeteria directly downstream. The dam failed during lunch hour. Vale had received safety certifications from German engineering firm TÜV SÜD weeks before the collapse — TÜV SÜD has faced separate legal proceedings in Germany for its certification conduct.","flags":["272_dead_majority_employees_contractors","cafeteria_destroyed_lunch_hour","tuv_sud_false_certification_proceedings"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"The Brumadinho and Mariana disasters together represent the two worst mining dam failures in Brazilian history and among the worst globally. The Mariana/Samarco disaster released toxic mining waste into the Doce River, destroying aquatic ecosystems for hundreds of kilometers and affecting the water supplies of hundreds of communities. Years after the Brumadinho failure, the Paraopeba River downstream from the dam site remains severely affected. Vale and BHP's reparations process for Mariana has been documented as inadequate and slow by affected communities and Brazilian prosecutors.","flags":["doce_river_destroyed_hundreds_kilometers","paraopeba_river_severely_affected","mariana_reparations_inadequate_slow"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"The Brumadinho dam failure — occurring on a dam that had received safety certification weeks earlier — generated intense scrutiny of Brazil's dam safety certification system and the relationships between mining companies and certification bodies. Brazilian prosecutors filed criminal charges against 16 Vale employees and executives, and against TÜV SÜD employees. Vale's political relationships with the Minas Gerais state government were scrutinized following both disasters.","flags":["criminal_charges_16_vale_employees_executives","tuv_sud_employees_charged","minas_gerais_government_relationship_scrutiny"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"Brumadinho: In 2021, Vale reached a $7 billion settlement with the state of Minas Gerais for reparations — the largest environmental settlement in Brazilian history. Criminal proceedings against Vale executives and TÜV SÜD employees continue in Brazilian courts as of 2026. Mariana/Samarco: Vale and BHP face ongoing litigation in Brazil and in UK courts — a UK class action involving approximately 720,000 claimants has proceeded despite Vale and BHP's jurisdictional challenges.","flags":["7b_brumadinho_minas_gerais_settlement_largest_brazil","criminal_proceedings_executives_ongoing","720000_uk_class_action_claimants"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Vale is listed on the NYSE and São Paulo Stock Exchange. The Brazilian government and Previ pension fund hold significant stakes. Vale uses standard mining company international structures for its global operations across Brazil, Canada, Indonesia, and other jurisdictions. No major criminal tax enforcement has been documented.","flags":["international_mining_structures","government_previ_partial_ownership"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Eduardo Bartolomeo has led Vale through the Brumadinho aftermath and reparations process. Former CEO Fabio Schvartsman was among the executives charged by Brazilian prosecutors in connection with Brumadinho — he had received internal warnings about dam safety risks prior to the failure. Schvartsman resigned days after the disaster.","flags":["schvartsman_charged_prosecutors","schvartsman_received_internal_warnings_pre_failure","resigned_days_after_disaster"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Vale's Samarco joint venture with BHP — the company behind the 2015 Mariana disaster — illustrates how major mining companies structure operations in ways that complicate liability attribution. Both Vale and BHP have contested full liability for Mariana in international courts. The UK class action representing 720,000 claimants is one of the largest environmental mass tort cases in English legal history.","flags":["bhp_joint_venture_liability_attribution_complication","uk_class_action_largest_environmental_english_history"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Brazilian prosecutors have alleged that Vale executives received internal engineering reports warning about Brumadinho dam stability in the months before failure — and that decisions were made to seek continued certification rather than to decommission the dam. TÜV SÜD employees have been alleged to have falsified or inadequately conducted the safety certification that declared the dam safe weeks before failure.","flags":["executive_warning_received_certification_sought_alleged","tuv_sud_falsified_certification_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"272 people died in the Brumadinho disaster — the deadliest mining dam failure in Brazilian history. 19 people died in the Mariana/Samarco disaster. Communities along the Doce and Paraopeba rivers experienced contamination of water supplies used for drinking, agriculture, and fishing. Long-term health monitoring of communities downstream from both disaster sites has documented elevated rates of skin conditions, respiratory illness, and mental health impacts from displacement and loss.","flags":["272_brumadinho_dead","19_mariana_dead","doce_paraopeba_water_contamination","downstream_health_monitoring_elevated_illness"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Vale is B2B infrastructure — consumers don't choose their iron ore producer. The systemic alternative is mandatory independent dam safety certification with criminal liability for false certification."],"healthier":["Advocacy for the International Commission on Large Dams (ICOLD) safety standards enforcement in Brazilian dam certification"],"diy":["The UK class action representing Mariana/Samarco victims is public record — claimants can register through their legal representatives","Support Brazilian dam safety reform: Brazilian environmental organization APEDEMA tracks dam safety legislation"]},"timeline":[{"year":2015,"event":"November: Samarco/Fundão dam failure in Mariana — 19 killed; 43 million cubic meters mining waste into Doce River; Vale and BHP jointly liable","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2019,"event":"January: Brumadinho dam failure — 272 killed; dam had received TÜV SÜD safety certification weeks earlier; majority of dead are Vale employees","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2019,"event":"CEO Schvartsman and other executives charged by Brazilian prosecutors; Schvartsman had received internal safety warnings","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"$7B settlement with Minas Gerais state — largest environmental settlement in Brazilian history","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2024,"event":"UK class action of 720,000 Mariana claimants proceeds; Vale and BHP jurisdictional challenges overruled","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"272 people were killed in Brumadinho. The majority were Vale employees eating lunch when the dam failed. Communities along both river systems were displaced by toxic waste, lost fishing and agricultural livelihoods, and face ongoing water contamination. The $7 billion Minas Gerais settlement funds reparations that affected communities have documented as arriving slowly and incompletely.","price_illusion":"Iron ore is priced on global commodity markets. The price does not include the cost of dam failures affecting communities downstream. The Brumadinho dam — which killed 272 people — had been certified safe. The certification was issued weeks before failure.","tax_math":"The $7 billion Brumadinho settlement is paid by Vale to the Minas Gerais state government for reparation distribution. The environmental cost of both disasters — remediation of two river systems, healthcare for affected communities — is borne by Brazilian public funds beyond the settlement.","wealth_velocity":"Vale's institutional shareholders — including global mining and index funds — receive iron ore production revenue. The communities downstream from Brumadinho and Mariana receive reparations documented as slow and incomplete."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Vale shareholders and iron ore buyers","how":"Iron ore production from mines whose dam safety costs were minimized through deficient certification and risk management"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"272 people killed at Brumadinho","how":"Died when a dam that had been certified safe weeks earlier failed during their lunch break"},{"group":"Communities along Doce and Paraopeba rivers","how":"Water contamination, livelihood destruction, displacement, ongoing health impacts from two of Brazil's worst environmental disasters"}],"the_gap":"Vale's Brumadinho dam was certified safe in November 2018. In January 2019 it collapsed. 272 people died. Most of them were eating lunch. Vale executives had received internal warnings about dam stability. The certifying firm TÜV SÜD faces criminal charges in Brazil. Vale paid $7 billion — the largest environmental settlement in Brazilian history. The river systems are still recovering. The criminal proceedings are still ongoing."}});
w('profiles_v4','dji',{"brand_name":"DJI","brand_slug":"dji","parent_company":"SZ DJI Technology Co., Ltd.","ultimate_parent":"Frank Wang (founder, controlling shareholder)","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"DJI CONTROLS 70% OF THE GLOBAL CONSUMER DRONE MARKET AND THE US GOVERNMENT SAYS ITS DRONES SEND DATA TO CHINA — CONGRESS HAS TRIED TO BAN THEM FOUR TIMES","executive_summary":"SZ DJI Technology Co., Ltd. is the world's dominant consumer and commercial drone manufacturer, controlling approximately 70% of the global consumer drone market and significant portions of the commercial and enterprise drone market. DJI is headquartered in Shenzhen, China and is subject to Chinese national security laws that require Chinese companies to cooperate with Chinese state intelligence. The US Department of Defense has placed DJI on its list of companies allegedly working with the Chinese military. The US Department of the Interior grounded its entire DJI drone fleet in 2019 citing data security concerns. Congress has repeatedly attempted to ban federal agencies from purchasing DJI drones. DJI drones have been documented used by both sides in the Russia-Ukraine conflict — raising questions about dual-use technology export controls.","verdict_tags":["70pct_global_consumer_drone_market","dod_chinese_military_company_list","dhs_data_security_alert","interior_department_fleet_grounded","russia_ukraine_both_sides_documented"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":false,"political":true,"tax":false,"health":false,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"DJI manufactures in Shenzhen, China — with the same labor conditions standard to Chinese electronics manufacturing. No major standalone DJI-specific labor violations have been documented beyond general Chinese manufacturing sector conditions. DJI employs approximately 14,000 people globally.","flags":["shenzhen_manufacturing_standard_conditions"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Drone manufacturing involves electronic components, batteries, and plastics with associated environmental concerns. DJI has made limited public environmental disclosures. No major environmental enforcement actions have been identified.","flags":["electronic_battery_manufacturing_environmental"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"DJI's Chinese ownership subjects it to China's National Intelligence Law — which requires Chinese companies to support, assist, and cooperate with state intelligence activities. The US DHS issued a May 2019 alert warning that DJI drones were transferring sensitive data to accessible servers. The US DoD placed DJI on its list of Chinese military companies in 2022. Four separate Congressional bills have attempted to ban federal DJI drone purchases. DJI has consistently denied that it shares data with the Chinese government.","flags":["china_national_intelligence_law_obligation","dhs_sensitive_data_alert_2019","dod_chinese_military_company_list_2022","four_congressional_ban_bills"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"DJI is on the US Entity List (export control restrictions) since 2020 — restricting US companies from selling technology to DJI without a license. DJI is on the DoD's Chinese military company list. The Interior Department grounded DJI drones in 2019. No criminal enforcement actions against DJI have been completed in the US, but the Entity List designation restricts technology transfer.","flags":["entity_list_since_2020","dod_chinese_military_company_list","interior_fleet_grounded_2019"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"DJI is a Chinese private company — its corporate structure is not publicly disclosed. The company's valuation was estimated at approximately $16 billion in its last disclosed funding round. Tax information is not publicly available for the private Chinese entity.","flags":["private_company_limited_disclosure"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"Frank Wang (Wang Tao) is DJI's founder and controlling shareholder. The company has maintained a relatively low executive public profile outside the drone industry. DJI has hired Western lobbyists and public relations firms to contest US government classifications and push back against federal purchase restrictions.","flags":["wang_tao_founder_controlling_shareholder","western_lobbyists_hired_us_classification_challenge"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"DJI's dominance — 70% global market share — means most commercial, agricultural, law enforcement, and media drone operations globally use DJI equipment. This creates documented intelligence collection infrastructure operated by a company subject to Chinese national security law across virtually every sector that uses drones.","flags":["70pct_market_intelligence_collection_infrastructure","law_enforcement_media_agricultural_dji_dependent"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"US defense and intelligence officials have alleged — in unclassified threat assessments — that DJI drones transmit flight path data, imagery, and operator information to servers accessible to the Chinese government. DJI has denied these allegations and has released firmware versions marketed as 'Government Edition' that purport to disable data transmission. Independent security researchers have found mixed results in auditing these claims.","flags":["dji_data_transmission_government_servers_alleged","government_edition_firmware_mixed_audit_results"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"DJI's documented concern is primarily national security and data sovereignty rather than direct health harm. Drone flight safety — the risk of drone-related injuries from equipment failure or pilot error — is a secondary concern managed through FAA regulation. No major health enforcement actions against DJI have been identified.","flags":["national_security_data_primary_concern"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Autel Robotics — US-distributed, non-Chinese-owned alternative; similar price points to DJI entry-level products","Skydio — US-based autonomous drone manufacturer; currently more expensive than DJI but US ownership"],"healthier":["Skydio — US company, no Chinese intelligence law obligation; government and enterprise users concerned about data security","Parrot — French manufacturer; EU-based; no US national security designation"],"diy":["If you use DJI for commercial or sensitive operations: DJI's 'Local Data Mode' disables internet connectivity during flights — enables operation without data transmission; verify independently","For hobbyist use: the data security concern is primarily relevant to sensitive sites and infrastructure; casual recreational use carries different risk profile"]},"timeline":[{"year":2006,"event":"Frank Wang founds DJI in Shenzhen dormitory room; begins drone development","severity":"neutral","source_url":""},{"year":2019,"event":"May: DHS issues security alert about DJI drones transferring data to accessible servers. Interior Department grounds DJI fleet.","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2020,"event":"DJI placed on US Entity List — restricts US technology sales to DJI","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2022,"event":"DoD places DJI on Chinese military company list","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2022,"event":"DJI drones documented used by both Russian and Ukrainian forces in conflict; dual-use export control questions raised","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Law enforcement agencies across the US that use DJI drones for surveillance — including border patrol, police departments, and emergency response — operate equipment subject to Chinese national security law data obligations. Communities surveilled by these drones have no practical visibility into where that data goes.","price_illusion":"DJI drones are priced as consumer and professional electronics products with standard commercial value propositions. The national security dimension — equipment operated by US law enforcement and critical infrastructure that is subject to Chinese intelligence law — is not reflected in the product price or marketing.","tax_math":"DJI is a private Chinese company with minimal public financial disclosure. Tax information is not available.","wealth_velocity":"DJI's estimated $16 billion valuation concentrates in Frank Wang and early investors. The surveillance data generated by DJI drones operated by law enforcement, agriculture, media, and consumers globally — on equipment subject to Chinese intelligence law — represents an information asset whose value and destination are not disclosed."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Frank Wang and DJI investors","how":"70% global drone market share built on hardware that the US government has documented as creating data security risks"},{"group":"Chinese state intelligence (alleged)","how":"Potential access to drone flight data, imagery, and operator information from equipment operated globally"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"US law enforcement and government agencies","how":"Operated equipment the DoD classified as Chinese military company products; Interior Department discovered after fleet deployment"}],"the_gap":"DJI controls 70% of the global drone market. The US Department of Homeland Security said their drones send data to servers accessible to the Chinese government. The Department of the Interior grounded their entire DJI fleet. The Department of Defense put DJI on the Chinese military company list. Congress has tried to ban them four times. DJI drones were used by both sides in Ukraine. DJI says they don't share data with China."}});
w('profiles_v4','primark',{"brand_name":"Primark","brand_slug":"primark","parent_company":"Associated British Foods plc","ultimate_parent":"Wittington Investments (Weston family, 54.5% ABF ownership)","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"PRIMARK SELLS T-SHIRTS FOR £3 AND JEANS FOR £7 — SOMEONE IS ABSORBING THE DIFFERENCE AND IT IS DOCUMENTED TO BE GARMENT WORKERS IN BANGLADESH","executive_summary":"Primark is an Irish-headquartered fast fashion retailer operating approximately 400 stores primarily in the UK, Ireland, and Europe, owned by Associated British Foods. Primark's price points — £3 t-shirts, £7 jeans, £1 socks — represent the extreme end of fast fashion pricing. The Clean Clothes Campaign, War on Want, and other organizations have documented that Primark's price points are structurally impossible without wage suppression and safety under-investment in its supplier factories. Primark had supplier factories in the Rana Plaza building that collapsed in Bangladesh in 2013 — killing 1,134 garment workers. Primark paid compensation to Rana Plaza victims and their families. The company does not have an e-commerce operation — it only sells in stores — which has insulated it from some digital marketing scrutiny.","verdict_tags":["rana_plaza_supplier_1134_dead","3_pound_t_shirt_structurally_impossible_without_wage_suppression","no_ecommerce_store_only","clean_clothes_campaign_documented","weston_family_abf_ownership"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":true,"political":false,"tax":true,"health":false,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Primark's supply chain spans approximately 800 factories in 30 countries. Rana Plaza (2013): Primark had supplier factories in the building; 1,134 garment workers killed. Primark paid compensation to affected workers and families — one of the few brands to do so. The structural critique: Primark's price points (£3 t-shirt) require margins at the bottom of the supply chain that independent researchers document as inconsistent with living wages. The Clean Clothes Campaign has documented that Primark's supplier monitoring has improved post-Rana Plaza but wage levels remain below living wage benchmarks in producing countries.","flags":["rana_plaza_supplier_factories_1134_dead","compensation_paid_one_of_few_brands","3_pound_t_shirt_structurally_impossible_living_wage","supplier_monitoring_improved_wages_still_below"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Primark's volume — approximately 400 million garment units annually across 400 stores — represents significant textile waste. The company has made commitments through its Primark Cares sustainability program. Unlike most fast fashion competitors, Primark has no e-commerce, which reduces last-mile delivery emissions but does not address production volume environmental impact.","flags":["400_million_garment_units_annually","primark_cares_commitments_volume_contradiction"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"Primark's parent ABF is controlled by the Weston family through Wittington Investments. The company has been a consistent target of fair fashion campaigners in the UK parliamentary system — UK MPs have raised Primark labor practices in parliamentary questions. Primark signed the Bangladesh Accord on Fire and Building Safety following Rana Plaza.","flags":["weston_family_abf_control","uk_parliamentary_questions_labor_practices","bangladesh_accord_signatory"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"No major criminal enforcement actions against Primark have been documented. Primark paid voluntary compensation to Rana Plaza victims — not pursuant to a legal judgment. Supply chain litigation: Primark has faced civil claims in multiple jurisdictions related to supplier factory conditions. UK Modern Slavery Act: Primark publishes annual transparency statements as required.","flags":["rana_plaza_voluntary_compensation","supply_chain_civil_claims","modern_slavery_act_statements"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Primark operates through Associated British Foods, which uses standard international holding arrangements. ABF's Weston family ownership through Wittington Investments includes significant charitable giving — the Garfield Weston Foundation is one of the UK's largest grant-making charities, funded by ABF dividends. No major criminal tax enforcement has been documented.","flags":["garfield_weston_foundation_abf_dividends","standard_international_holding_arrangements"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"Primark CEO Paul Marchant leads the company. The Weston family's control through Wittington Investments and the Garfield Weston Foundation creates a governance structure where Primark's profits fund charitable giving — a combination that coexists with the documented supply chain labor conditions. No Primark executive has been criminally charged for supply chain violations.","flags":["weston_family_charitable_giving_primark_profits","no_executive_charges"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Primark's position at the extreme low-price end of fast fashion — below H&M, Zara, and even Shein on some items — represents the most compressed version of the fast fashion supply chain margin model. Its supplier factory network overlaps with the same Bangladesh, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka ecosystems documented for labor conditions across the fast fashion sector.","flags":["below_hm_zara_shein_price_points","overlapping_supplier_ecosystem"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"The Clean Clothes Campaign has alleged that Primark's price points are structurally impossible to achieve at documented factory gate prices consistent with living wages and safe working conditions — and that Primark's supplier auditing, while improved post-Rana Plaza, cannot verify conditions at the level of specificity that would confirm living wage compliance.","flags":["price_points_structurally_inconsistent_living_wage_alleged","audit_verification_insufficient_specificity_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Rana Plaza (2013): 1,134 garment workers killed in building collapse. Workers had reported cracks in the building the day before; factory managers ordered workers in anyway. Primark's suppliers were among the brands with confirmed factories in the building. Ongoing: garment workers in Primark's supply chain face documented occupational health hazards from textile chemicals, repetitive stress, and unsafe factory conditions in producing countries with variable regulatory enforcement.","flags":["rana_plaza_1134_dead_primark_supplier_confirmed","cracks_reported_managers_ordered_in_anyway","textile_chemical_repetitive_stress_ongoing"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Secondhand clothing: charity shops, Vinted, Depop — genuinely cheaper on per-wear basis than Primark's price-per-garment","Capsule wardrobe approach: fewer, more durable items typically cheaper over a 2-year horizon than Primark volume purchasing"],"healthier":["The True Cost documentary available on streaming — explains the supply chain behind £3 t-shirts more accessibly than academic research","Fair trade certified clothing brands — People Tree, Thought Clothing — with verified supply chain standards"],"diy":["Primark is one of the brands on the Fashion Checker (fashionchecker.org) — the tool shows whether brands pay living wages in their supply chains","Mending, altering, and extending garment life is the most direct individual response to fast fashion's waste and labor model"]},"timeline":[{"year":2013,"event":"Rana Plaza collapse: 1,134 dead; Primark suppliers confirmed in building; Primark pays voluntary compensation to victims","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2013,"event":"Bangladesh Accord on Fire and Building Safety: Primark among signatories","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2019,"event":"Primark launches 'Primark Cares' sustainability program; targets for sustainable materials","severity":"moderate","source_url":""},{"year":2023,"event":"Clean Clothes Campaign documents ongoing wage below living wage benchmarks in Primark supply chain despite Cares commitments","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Garment communities in Bangladesh, Pakistan, and Sri Lanka producing for Primark live in conditions that independent researchers document as below living wage — wages insufficient for housing, food, healthcare, and education for their families. Rana Plaza demonstrated the physical safety endpoint of building and safety cost pressure on suppliers.","price_illusion":"The £3 t-shirt price is real. The full cost includes: garment worker wages documented below living wage in producing countries; fire and building safety deficiencies from supplier cost pressure; textile waste from volume production; and the 1,134 people who died in the Rana Plaza building producing for fast fashion brands.","tax_math":"ABF's profits — including Primark — fund the Garfield Weston Foundation's charitable giving. This structure means Primark's supply chain labor model partially funds UK philanthropic activity.","wealth_velocity":"The Weston family's wealth — built through ABF and Primark — includes substantial philanthropic giving through Garfield Weston. Garment workers in Primark's supply chain earning below living wages produce the goods that generate those philanthropic resources."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Primark shoppers","how":"Genuine price savings on clothing — £3 t-shirts are real; the gap is paid elsewhere in the supply chain"},{"group":"Weston family and ABF shareholders","how":"Margins from extreme fast fashion pricing enabled by supply chain wage compression and safety under-investment"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Garment workers in Bangladesh, Pakistan, Sri Lanka","how":"Wages documented below living wage; 1,134 killed at Rana Plaza in suppliers producing for Primark and other brands"}],"the_gap":"Primark sells t-shirts for £3. Jeans for £7. Socks for £1. Someone is absorbing the difference between what things cost to make at a living wage and what Primark pays. The Clean Clothes Campaign says it's the workers. Primark had suppliers in Rana Plaza. 1,134 people died. Primark paid compensation. The price is still £3."}});
w('profiles_v4','bosch',{"brand_name":"Bosch","brand_slug":"bosch","parent_company":"Robert Bosch GmbH","ultimate_parent":"Robert Bosch Stiftung (charitable foundation, 94% voting rights)","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"BOSCH SUPPLIED THE DEFEAT DEVICE SOFTWARE FOR 11 MILLION VOLKSWAGEN DIESELS AND PAID $327 MILLION — IT IS OWNED BY A CHARITABLE FOUNDATION THAT MAKES GIVING MONEY AWAY LOOK GOOD","executive_summary":"Robert Bosch GmbH is the world's largest automotive supplier, headquartered in Stuttgart, Germany. Bosch supplied the engine management software used in Volkswagen's diesel defeat device — the software installed in approximately 11 million vehicles that detected emissions testing conditions and reduced NOx output only during tests. Bosch settled US civil claims related to this software for $327.5 million in 2017. Bosch's corporate structure is unique: 94% of its voting rights are held by the Robert Bosch Stiftung (charitable foundation), which uses Bosch dividends to fund healthcare, education, and democracy programs. This structure — where a major industrial company is controlled by a charitable foundation — provides both tax advantages and insulation from standard shareholder accountability.","verdict_tags":["327m_defeat_device_software_supplier","bosch_supplied_vw_11_million_vehicles","robert_bosch_stiftung_foundation_94pct_voting","foundation_structure_tax_advantage","automotive_worlds_largest_supplier"],"concern_flags":{"labor":false,"environmental":true,"political":false,"tax":true,"health":true,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Bosch employs approximately 420,000 people globally — the largest Bosch workforce in Germany, with significant operations in India, China, and the US. No major documented systemic labor violations have been identified as a primary concern relative to its defeat device supplier role.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Bosch's defeat device software — supplied to VW for use in 11 million diesel vehicles — enabled NOx emissions 40 times the legal limit during real-world driving. While Bosch was a supplier rather than the vehicle manufacturer, it provided the technical mechanism for the fraud. Bosch has also been involved in the broader European diesel emissions scandal affecting multiple manufacturers beyond VW.","flags":["defeat_device_40x_nox_supplier_mechanism","european_diesel_scandal_broader_involvement"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"Bosch's foundation structure provides governance and political insulation unavailable to publicly traded companies. The Robert Bosch Stiftung's charitable mission — and the reputational halo it provides — has complicated public accountability discussions about Bosch's role in the diesel emissions scandal.","flags":["foundation_structure_accountability_insulation","charitable_halo_complicates_accountability"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2017: Bosch settled US civil claims related to its defeat device software supply to VW for $327.5 million — without admitting wrongdoing. Bosch was not criminally charged in the US for its role. German prosecutors investigated Bosch executives for their role in the defeat device; some prosecutions proceeded. Bosch faced separate claims in European jurisdictions for defeat device-related conduct.","flags":["327_5m_us_civil_settlement_no_admission","no_us_criminal_charges_supplier","german_executive_prosecutions_some","european_jurisdiction_claims"],"sources":["https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-bosch/bosch-to-pay-327-5-million-in-u-s-settlements-over-vw-emissions-scandal-idUSKBN14X1EJ"]},"tax":{"summary":"The Robert Bosch Stiftung structure — where a charitable foundation holds 94% of voting rights — provides significant tax advantages. Foundation income used for charitable purposes is tax-exempt in Germany. The structure also means Bosch is not subject to the same shareholder pressure on profit distribution that would apply to a publicly traded company. Robert Bosch GmbH itself pays German corporate taxes on its industrial operations.","flags":["foundation_94pct_voting_tax_exempt_income","no_shareholder_profit_pressure","corporate_tax_paid_on_industrial_operations"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"Stefan Hartung leads Bosch as chairman of the board of management. The Robert Bosch Stiftung's governance — separate from Bosch GmbH's management — means the foundation's charitable board has ultimate voting authority. No Bosch executive was criminally charged in the US defeat device settlement. German prosecutions of specific Bosch engineers involved in defeat device development have proceeded with varying outcomes.","flags":["foundation_board_ultimate_voting_authority","no_us_executive_charges","german_engineer_prosecutions_varying"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Bosch is the automotive supplier whose defeat device software connected it to VW, Audi, Porsche, and ultimately to the entire German diesel scandal. The same Bosch engine management software was used across multiple European manufacturers. Bosch is simultaneously a major supplier to virtually every global automaker — its market position made it both the mechanism of the fraud and difficult to exclude from the industry.","flags":["software_used_multiple_european_manufacturers","impossible_to_exclude_market_position"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Plaintiff attorneys in US civil cases alleged that Bosch engineers knew the defeat device software would be used to cheat on emissions tests — not merely as an engine calibration tool — and provided technical assistance knowing its intended deceptive use. Bosch contested this characterization in settling without admission of wrongdoing.","flags":["engineers_knew_intended_use_defeat_alleged","technical_assistance_knowing_deceptive_use_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Bosch's defeat device software enabled 11 million VW vehicles to emit NOx at up to 40 times the legal limit during real-world driving. The estimated 59 premature US deaths and 1,200 asthma cases attributed to the VW defeat device — and higher European estimates — are downstream health consequences of software Bosch supplied. Bosch's role as supplier rather than vehicle manufacturer does not change the health consequences of the software it provided.","flags":["40x_nox_11_million_vehicles_bosch_software","59_us_premature_deaths_downstream_of_bosch_software"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Bosch is a B2B supplier — consumers don't directly choose Bosch. The consumer-facing alternative is choosing EVs, which eliminate diesel components entirely."],"healthier":["Electric vehicles eliminate the diesel NOx concern at its source — demand reduction for diesel drivetrains reduces the market for defeat device-enabled engine management software"],"diy":["If you have a VW, Audi, or Porsche diesel from 2009-2016: check your VIN at the EPA VW settlement website — extended warranty coverage may still be available"]},"timeline":[{"year":2006,"event":"Bosch begins developing engine management software that VW will use as defeat device basis","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2015,"event":"Defeat device disclosed; Bosch's role as software supplier revealed","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2017,"event":"Bosch pays $327.5M US civil settlement; no criminal charges; no admission of wrongdoing","severity":"critical","source_url":"https://www.reuters.com/article/us-volkswagen-emissions-bosch/bosch-to-pay-327-5-million-in-u-s-settlements-over-vw-emissions-scandal-idUSKBN14X1EJ"}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Communities near highways absorbed the 40x NOx emissions from 11 million VW vehicles running Bosch's defeat device software. Bosch's role — as technical enabler — is legally distinct from VW's role as vehicle manufacturer but not environmentally distinct.","price_illusion":"Bosch products appear in vehicles marketed with clean diesel credentials. The engine management software Bosch supplied was the technical mechanism that made those credentials fraudulent.","tax_math":"The Robert Bosch Stiftung's charitable structure means foundation income is tax-exempt. Bosch GmbH's industrial profits fund the foundation. The foundation's charitable giving — in healthcare, education, and democracy — is partially funded by profits from a company that supplied defeat device software.","wealth_velocity":"Bosch is not publicly traded. The Robert Bosch Stiftung holds voting control and receives dividends that fund charitable programs. There are no individual shareholder beneficiaries in the traditional sense — which is both the most admirable and most accountability-insulating aspect of the structure."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"VW and other automakers using Bosch defeat device software","how":"Emissions compliance at test time without the cost of actual NOx reduction technology; sold diesel vehicles with fraudulent clean credentials"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Communities near highways","how":"40x legal NOx limit emissions from 11 million vehicles running Bosch's defeat device software"}],"the_gap":"Bosch wrote the software. VW used it to cheat on emissions tests in 11 million cars. Bosch paid $327 million. They didn't admit wrongdoing. No criminal charges were filed against Bosch in the US. Bosch is owned by a charitable foundation. The foundation funds healthcare and education with Bosch's dividends. The software enabled emissions that researchers estimate caused 59 premature deaths in the United States."}});
w('profiles_v4','haier',{"brand_name":"Haier","brand_slug":"haier","parent_company":"Haier Smart Home Co., Ltd.","ultimate_parent":"Haier Group Corporation (Chinese state-linked enterprise)","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"HAIER CONTROLS GE APPLIANCES AND FISHER & PAYKEL — MOST AMERICANS BUYING A GE FRIDGE DON'T KNOW THEY'RE BUYING FROM A CHINESE STATE-LINKED COMPANY","executive_summary":"Haier Smart Home Co., Ltd. is China's largest home appliance manufacturer and the world's largest home appliance brand by retail volume. Through its 2016 acquisition of GE Appliances for $5.6 billion and its 2012 acquisition of New Zealand's Fisher & Paykel, Haier controls major appliance brands that most consumers in North America and Australasia do not recognize as Chinese-owned. Haier Group — Haier's parent — is a Chinese state-linked enterprise with complex government relationships. Haier's manufacturing operations in China have been subject to documented labor condition concerns. The company's data practices — as a manufacturer of smart home appliances including refrigerators, washing machines, and air conditioners that collect usage data — have drawn scrutiny given Chinese data security law obligations.","verdict_tags":["ge_appliances_5_6b_acquisition_chinese_owned","fisher_paykel_new_zealand_chinese_owned","state_linked_enterprise","smart_appliance_data_collection_china_law","brand_ownership_opacity_consumers"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":false,"political":true,"tax":false,"health":false,"legal":false},"labor":{"summary":"Haier's Chinese manufacturing operations have documented labor conditions consistent with Chinese electronics and appliance manufacturing — including working hours above ILO standards, wages near regional minimums, and limited independent union representation under China's ACFTU-controlled labor structure. No major standalone Haier-specific labor violations at the scale of some peers have been documented publicly.","flags":["chinese_manufacturing_standard_conditions","acftu_controlled_labor_structure"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Haier manufactures home appliances — refrigerants, plastics, metals, and electronics. The company has made energy efficiency commitments aligned with Chinese regulatory requirements. No major environmental enforcement actions have been identified as a primary concern.","flags":["refrigerant_plastic_metal_electronic_manufacturing"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary":"Haier Group's relationship with Chinese state entities — as a company that grew with significant state support and remains subject to Chinese national security and data laws — creates documented tensions with Western regulatory environments. The GE Appliances acquisition was reviewed by CFIUS (Committee on Foreign Investment in the US); it was approved. As Chinese data security and national security laws have expanded, Haier's smart appliance data collection in Western homes has drawn scrutiny from European and US data protection researchers.","flags":["cfius_reviewed_approved","chinese_national_security_law_applies","smart_appliance_data_collection_western_homes","european_us_data_protection_scrutiny"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"No major criminal enforcement actions against Haier have been documented in Western jurisdictions. CFIUS approved the GE Appliances acquisition in 2016. Haier faces the same Chinese data security law compliance obligations as all Chinese companies — including obligations to cooperate with Chinese state intelligence requests. No formal US enforcement action has been taken against Haier for data practices.","flags":["cfius_approved_2016","chinese_data_security_law_cooperation_obligation","no_us_enforcement_action"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Haier Smart Home is listed on the Shanghai Stock Exchange and the Hong Kong Stock Exchange. Haier Group is the ultimate parent and has complex state-linked ownership structures standard to major Chinese industrial enterprises. GE Appliances — as a US subsidiary — pays US corporate taxes on US operations.","flags":["shanghai_hong_kong_listed","state_linked_complex_ownership"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Liang Haishan leads Haier Smart Home. Founder Zhang Ruimin — who built Haier from a failing refrigerator factory — retired from day-to-day management. Zhang built Haier's RenDanHeYi management model — a microenterprise ecosystem approach widely studied in business schools — while the company grew into the world's largest appliance brand.","flags":["zhang_ruimin_founder_rendanheyi_model","liang_haishan_ceo"],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Haier's acquisition of GE Appliances made it the US market leader in major appliances under the GE, Café, Monogram, Profile, and Hotpoint brands — brands American consumers associate with a US heritage company. Haier similarly acquired Fisher & Paykel — a beloved New Zealand appliance brand — making it Chinese-owned without the brand identity reflecting this. The ownership opacity is documented as a deliberate positioning strategy.","flags":["ge_cafe_monogram_profile_hotpoint_all_chinese_owned","fisher_paykel_nz_brand_chinese_owned","ownership_opacity_deliberate_positioning"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"Cybersecurity researchers have alleged that Haier's smart appliance firmware — including GE Appliances smart products — transmits usage data to servers in China, and that the data collection scope exceeds what is disclosed in consumer privacy notices. Haier has disputed these characterizations. The obligation under Chinese national security law to cooperate with state intelligence means the relevant question is not only what data Haier collects but what it could be required to share.","flags":["smart_appliance_firmware_china_server_data_alleged","data_collection_scope_exceeds_disclosure_alleged","national_security_law_required_sharing_question"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Haier's primary documented concerns are geopolitical and data-related rather than direct health harm. No major product safety recalls at the scale of some peers have been documented. Standard appliance safety regulations apply to GE Appliances in the US.","flags":["geopolitical_data_primary_concern"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Whirlpool (US-owned) — Maytag, KitchenAid, Whirlpool brand appliances; different data profile","LG (South Korean) — different geopolitical risk profile; South Korea not subject to Chinese data security law"],"healthier":["For smart appliance data concerns: conventional non-connected appliances eliminate data collection entirely","Electrolux (Swedish) or Miele (German) — European manufacturers with EU data protection law obligations"],"diy":["Check your GE Appliance model's smart connectivity settings — most can be used without WiFi connection, eliminating data transmission","The GE Appliances website discloses Haier's ownership — this information is available but not prominently marketed"]},"timeline":[{"year":2012,"event":"Haier acquires Fisher & Paykel (New Zealand) — brand identity remains NZ-associated","severity":"moderate","source_url":""},{"year":2016,"event":"Haier acquires GE Appliances for $5.6B — GE brand identity remains US-associated; CFIUS approves","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2017,"event":"China's National Intelligence Law expands — requires Chinese companies to support state intelligence activities","severity":"high","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"Cybersecurity researchers begin examining Haier smart appliance data practices; findings published","severity":"moderate","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"American consumers purchasing GE-branded appliances — trusting a US heritage brand — are purchasing from a Chinese state-linked enterprise subject to Chinese national security law data obligations. The brand trust built over decades by the American GE company was transferred to Haier with the acquisition.","price_illusion":"GE Appliances are priced and marketed as premium American appliances with implied quality and safety standards. The Chinese ownership and associated data security law obligations are not reflected in the brand's marketing or positioning.","tax_math":"GE Appliances as a US subsidiary pays US corporate taxes on US operations. Profits beyond those retained in GE Appliances can be repatriated to Haier in China, subject to applicable withholding taxes.","wealth_velocity":"Haier Group's state-linked ownership means profits from the world's largest appliance business — including GE Appliances' US revenue — flow through a complex Chinese state-enterprise structure."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Haier and Haier Group shareholders","how":"Acquired GE Appliances brand trust and market position for $5.6B; ongoing US revenue from consumers who may not know the ownership"},{"group":"GE shareholders","how":"$5.6B sale of appliance division at favorable valuation"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"GE Appliance consumers who care about data ownership","how":"Purchase appliances subject to Chinese national security law data obligations; brand association does not reflect ownership"}],"the_gap":"GE Appliances has been Chinese-owned since 2016. Fisher & Paykel has been Chinese-owned since 2012. Most consumers buying a GE refrigerator in the United States do not know they are buying from a company owned by Haier Group — a Chinese state-linked enterprise subject to Chinese national security law. The GE brand was not changed. The data obligations were."}});
w('profiles_v4','lindt',{"brand_name":"Lindt","brand_slug":"lindt","parent_company":"Chocoladefabriken Lindt & Sprüngli AG","ultimate_parent":"Chocoladefabriken Lindt & Sprüngli AG (Swiss family influence)","overall_concern_level":"moderate","profile_type":"database","generated_headline":"LINDT SELLS $5 CHOCOLATE BARS AND MARKETS ITSELF AS PREMIUM — ITS COCOA COMES FROM THE SAME IVORY COAST SUPPLY CHAIN WITH DOCUMENTED CHILD LABOR AS HERSHEY AND NESTLÉ","executive_summary":"Chocoladefabriken Lindt & Sprüngli AG is Switzerland's premier premium chocolate manufacturer, operating the Lindt and Ghirardelli brands. Lindt markets itself as a premium chocolate brand — positioned above the mass market through higher prices, distinctive gold rabbit and Master Chocolatier branding, and Swiss heritage. However, Lindt's cocoa supply chain sources from the same West African — primarily Ivory Coast and Ghana — smallholder ecosystem documented across the chocolate industry for child labor, hazardous agricultural work, and poverty-level farmer incomes. A 2020 class action filed in the US alleged Lindt's 'no child labor' claims were false advertising. Lindt has been named in the same industry-wide child labor litigation that has implicated Nestlé, Mars, Mondelez, Hershey, and others sourcing West African cocoa.","verdict_tags":["cocoa_child_labor_ivory_coast_supply_chain","no_child_labor_claim_false_advertising_2020","same_ecosystem_as_nestle_mars_hershey","premium_brand_same_supply_chain_concerns","harkin_engel_protocol_failed_all_brands"],"concern_flags":{"labor":true,"environmental":false,"political":false,"tax":true,"health":false,"legal":true},"labor":{"summary":"Lindt's West African cocoa supply chain — primarily Ivory Coast — shares the documented child labor ecosystem with Nestlé, Mars, Hershey, and Mondelez. The 2020 US class action alleged Lindt's marketing claims of no child labor were false advertising given the documented conditions in its supply chain. The Harkin-Engel Protocol (2001) committed the chocolate industry to eliminate child labor by 2005 — a target missed by every major brand. An independent study commissioned by the US Department of Labor found child labor persisting across the Ivory Coast cocoa sector serving all major brands.","flags":["ivory_coast_child_labor_supply_chain","2020_no_child_labor_false_advertising_claim","harkin_engel_2001_commitment_missed_all_brands","dol_study_child_labor_persists"],"sources":[]},"environmental":{"summary":"Cocoa farming in Ivory Coast and Ghana is associated with documented deforestation as smallholder farmers expand into forest land to increase production. Lindt has made sustainable sourcing commitments including traceability programs. No major standalone environmental enforcement actions have been identified.","flags":["cocoa_deforestation_ivory_coast_ghana","sustainable_sourcing_traceability_commitments"],"sources":[]},"political":{"summary": "Lindt's political profile is primarily through its supply chain advocacy — the company participates in industry coalitions working on sustainable cocoa. No major standalone political concerns comparable to peers have been identified.","flags":["industry_coalition_sustainable_cocoa"],"sources":[]},"legal":{"summary":"2020: US class action filed against Lindt alleging false advertising — specifically that Lindt's marketing claims of sourcing cocoa from farms with no child labor were materially misleading given documented conditions in its Ivory Coast supply chain. No formal US criminal enforcement action has been completed against Lindt for supply chain labor practices.","flags":["2020_us_class_action_false_advertising","no_child_labor_claim_challenged"],"sources":[]},"tax":{"summary":"Lindt is incorporated in Switzerland — benefiting from Swiss cantonal tax arrangements. The company is listed on the Swiss Exchange. No major criminal tax enforcement actions have been documented.","flags":["swiss_cantonal_tax_incorporation"],"sources":[]},"executives":{"summary":"CEO Adalbert Leyendecker leads Lindt. The company's Swiss executive team has maintained the premium brand positioning while facing supply chain scrutiny consistent with the broader chocolate industry. No Lindt executive has been criminally charged for supply chain violations.","flags":[],"sources":[]},"connections":{"summary":"Lindt's supply chain connects it to the same Ivory Coast cocoa farming ecosystem as Nestlé, Mars, Mondelez, Hershey, and every major chocolate brand. The child labor documentation applies to this ecosystem broadly — not to specific Lindt-exclusive farms. The premium pricing Lindt commands does not provide premium supply chain accountability relative to mass-market peers.","flags":["same_ecosystem_all_major_chocolate_brands","premium_price_no_premium_accountability"],"sources":[]},"allegations":{"disclaimer":"The following are allegations and unproven claims documented in credible sources but not adjudicated.","summary":"The 2020 class action alleged that Lindt's marketing — including claims that its chocolates were sourced from farms adhering to strict no-child-labor standards — was materially misleading because Lindt sources from the same Ivory Coast supply chain where child labor is documented by independent research. Lindt has disputed the characterization.","flags":["marketing_claims_misleading_supply_chain_conditions_alleged"],"sources":[]},"health_record":{"summary":"Child labor in cocoa farming involves hazardous agricultural work — machete use, pesticide exposure, heavy lifting — performed by children as young as 5-6 years in some documented cases. The hazardous child labor documentation spans the Ivory Coast cocoa sector serving all major chocolate brands including Lindt.","flags":["machete_pesticide_heavy_lifting_child_hazardous_work","children_5_6_documented_cases"],"sources":[]},"alternatives":{"cheaper":["Tony's Chocolonely — mission-driven brand with independently verified child-labor-free sourcing; similar price to Lindt","Divine Chocolate — farmer-owned cooperative chocolate; Fairtrade certified"],"healthier":["Tony's Chocolonely — most independently verified cocoa supply chain of any major chocolate brand","Fairtrade certified chocolate — independent certification with farmer income standards"],"diy":["The Good Chocolate Guide (goodchocolateguide.org) independently rates chocolate brands on supply chain standards — Lindt's rating can be compared against alternatives","Tony's Chocolonely's annual report provides the most detailed public cocoa supply chain data of any chocolate company — useful benchmark"]},"timeline":[{"year":1845,"event":"Lindt & Sprüngli founded in Zurich; inventor of the conching process that defines modern smooth chocolate","severity":"neutral","source_url":""},{"year":2001,"event":"Harkin-Engel Protocol: chocolate industry commits to eliminate child labor from cocoa supply chains by 2005 — commitment missed","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2020,"event":"US class action filed against Lindt and other chocolate brands for false advertising — 'no child labor' claims challenged","severity":"critical","source_url":""},{"year":2021,"event":"US Supreme Court dismisses Nestlé/Cargill child slavery case on jurisdiction — industry liability pattern continues unresolved","severity":"high","source_url":""}],"community_impact":{"displacement":"Ivory Coast cocoa farming communities — where children perform hazardous agricultural work as documented by NORC at the University of Chicago — absorb the cost of supplying cocoa at prices that all major chocolate brands, including Lindt, have not increased sufficiently to fund farm-level living wages and education alternatives to child labor.","price_illusion":"Lindt charges a premium for Swiss chocolatier heritage and quality. The premium price does not translate to premium supply chain accountability — Lindt's cocoa comes from the same Ivory Coast ecosystem documented for child labor as mass-market brands costing a fraction of Lindt's price point.","tax_math":"Swiss incorporation provides favorable tax treatment. The price premium Lindt commands — above mass-market chocolate — generates additional margin that is not documented to translate into higher farmer prices or supply chain labor improvements proportional to the premium.","wealth_velocity":"Lindt is listed on the Swiss Exchange. Revenue from premium-priced chocolate sourced from supply chains with documented child labor concentrates in Swiss shareholder returns."},"cost_absorption":{"who_benefited":[{"group":"Lindt shareholders","how":"Premium pricing on chocolate sourced from the same documented child labor ecosystem as mass-market brands; brand premium not reflected in supply chain investment"}],"who_paid":[{"group":"Ivory Coast child cocoa workers","how":"Hazardous agricultural labor — machetes, pesticides, heavy lifting — in cocoa farms supplying Lindt and every other major chocolate brand"}],"the_gap":"Lindt charges $5 for a chocolate bar and markets itself as premium. The cocoa comes from Ivory Coast. The same Ivory Coast supply chain that Nestlé and Hershey use. The same child labor that all of them promised to eliminate in 2001. They all missed the deadline. Lindt's marketing said no child labor. A class action said that was false advertising. The children are still working."}});

